<main role=\"main\">\n        <!-- Secondary header starts -->\n<div class=\"secondary-header cf\" id=\"wd-secondary-header\">\n    <!-- Branded journal header starts -->\n<div class=\"big-branded\">\n\n    <div class=\"publication-name\" id=\"wd-pub-name\">\n\t<div class=\"publication-title\" itemprop=\"name\" itemid=\"periodical\">\n\t\t\t\t<!-- Journal image link tile starts -->\n<!-- Logo tile starts -->\n<a href=\"/journal/0004-637X\" itemprop=\"url\">\n    <img src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/8febf88b-d09c-11e5-b0b6-759f86a2008e/apj-2016.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The Astrophysical Journal\">\n</a>\n<!-- Logo tile ends -->\n<!-- Journal image link tile ends -->\n</div>\n\t\t</div>\n    <div class=\"partner-logos m-hide\" id=\"wd-partner-logos\">\n            <div class=\"partner-logo-alignment\">\n                <!-- Partner logo tile starts -->\n<a href=\"\" class=\"overlay-launch\">\n    <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/8a2230b8-d09c-11e5-b0b6-759f86a2008e/aas-2018.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The American Astronomical Society, find out more\">\n</a>\n<span class=\"overlay-set\">\n    <div class=\"tint-screen\"></div>\n    <div class=\"overlay-panel\">\n        <a title=\"Close\"  class=\"close-icon close-overlay\" tabindex=\"0\" role=\"button\" aria-describedby=\"close-icon-description\"><span class=\"icon-close\"></span></a>\n        <p id=\"close-icon-description\" class=\"offscreen-hidden\">Click here to close this overlay, or press the \"Escape\" key on your keyboard.</p>\n        <div class=\"overlay-img\">\n            <a href=\"\">\n                <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/8a2230b8-d09c-11e5-b0b6-759f86a2008e/aas-2018.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The American Astronomical Society, find out more\">\n            </a>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"overlay-text\">\n            <p>The American Astronomical Society (AAS), established in 1899 and based in Washington, DC, is the major organization of professional astronomers in North America. Its membership of about 7,000 individuals also includes physicists, mathematicians, geologists, engineers, and others whose research and educational interests lie within the broad spectrum of subjects comprising contemporary astronomy. The mission of the AAS is to enhance and share humanity's scientific understanding of the universe.</p> <p><a href=\"https://aas.org/\">https://aas.org/</a></div>\n        <p class=\"ta-c mt-1 mb-2\"><a href=\"\"></a></p>\n    </div>\n</span>\n<!-- Partner logo tile ends -->\n\n<!-- Partner logo tile starts -->\n<a href=\"\" class=\"overlay-launch\">\n    <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/7ebd1b32-0439-11e9-b401-cfe9679c40e3/iop-2016.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The Institute of Physics, find out more\">\n</a>\n<span class=\"overlay-set\">\n    <div class=\"tint-screen\"></div>\n    <div class=\"overlay-panel\">\n        <a title=\"Close\"  class=\"close-icon close-overlay\" tabindex=\"0\" role=\"button\" aria-describedby=\"close-icon-description\"><span class=\"icon-close\"></span></a>\n        <p id=\"close-icon-description\" class=\"offscreen-hidden\">Click here to close this overlay, or press the \"Escape\" key on your keyboard.</p>\n        <div class=\"overlay-img\">\n            <a href=\"\">\n                <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/7ebd1b32-0439-11e9-b401-cfe9679c40e3/iop-2016.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The Institute of Physics, find out more\">\n            </a>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"overlay-text\">\n            <p>The Institute of Physics (IOP) is a leading scientific society promoting physics and bringing physicists together for the benefit of all. It has a worldwide membership of around 50 000 comprising physicists from all sectors, as well as those with an interest in physics. It works to advance physics research, application and education; and engages with policy makers and the public to develop awareness and understanding of physics. Its publishing company, IOP Publishing, is a world leader in professional scientific communications.</p> <p><a href=\"https://www.iop.org\">https://www.iop.org</a></p></div>\n        <p class=\"ta-c mt-1 mb-2\"><a href=\"\"></a></p>\n    </div>\n</span>\n<!-- Partner logo tile ends -->\n\n<p></p>\n                </div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n<!-- Branded journal header ends -->\n</div> <!-- end secondary-header -->\n<!-- Secondary header ends --><div class=\"da1-da2\" itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/ScholarlyArticle\" id=\"page-content\">\n            <div class=\"da1 ta1 article-head\">\n                <!-- Start Eyebrow block, containing Surtitle and Labels -->\n<div class=\"eyebrow\">\n\t<!-- Start Collection Labels -->\n    <!-- End Collection Labels --> </div>\n<!-- End Eyebrow block -->\n\n<h1 itemprop=\"headline\" class=\"wd-jnl-art-title\">A SPECTROSCOPIC SURVEY OF THE FIELDS OF 28 STRONG GRAVITATIONAL LENSES: THE GROUP CATALOG</h1>\n\n<p class=\"mb-0\">\n\t<span data-authors=\"\">\n\t\t<span itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\" itemprop=\"author\" class=\"nowrap\"><span itemprop=\"name\">Michelle L. class=\"da1 ta1\">\n                <!-- Start Linked Articles note -->\n\t<!-- End Linked Articles note -->\n<!-- Article information starts. This includes author emails, affiliations, article published date, doi etc. -->\n\t<div class=\"reveal-container reveal-closed reveal-plus-icon bdt-1 wd-jnl-art-article-info-wrapper\">\n      \t<div class=\"replica-h3 mt-0\">\n        \t<a id=\"wd-article-info-accordion\" href=\"#\" class=\"reveal-trigger\" data-reveal-label-alt=\"Hide article information\">Article information</a>\n      \t</div>\n      \t<div class=\"reveal-content\">\n        \t<div class=\"article-meta\">\n          \t\t<!-- Start Affiliations --><div class=\"wd-jnl-art-author-affiliations\"><div class=\"replica-h4\">Author affiliations</div><p class=\"mb-05\"><sup>1</sup>   Steward Observatory, University of Arizona, 933 North Cherry Avenue, Tucson, AZ 85721, USA</p><p class=\"mb-05\"><sup>2</sup>   Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Physics Division L-210, 7000 East Avenue, Livermore, CA 94550, USA</p><p class=\"mb-05\"><sup>3</sup>   Space Telescope Science Institute, 3700 San Martin Drive, Baltimore, MD 21218, USA</p><p class=\"mb-05\"><sup>4</sup>   Department of Physics and Astronomy, Texas A&amp;M University-Commerce, Commerce, TX, 75428, USA</p><p class=\"mb-05\"><sup>5</sup>   Department of Physics and Astronomy, Rutgers University, 136 Frelinghuysen Road, Piscataway, NJ 08854, USA</p></div><!-- End Affiliations --><!-- Start ORCIDs --><div class=\"wd-jnl-art-author-orcid-list\"><div class=\"replica-h4\">ORCID iDs</div><p class=\"mb-05\"><span itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\" itemprop=\"author\" class=\"nowrap\"><span itemprop=\"name\">Ann I. <span class=\"icon-newtab\">\n            </a></p>\n        </div>\n\n    <!-- End Email Alert -->\n<!-- End Email Alert --><!-- Start Citation Alert Link -->\n                        <p>\n<div class=\"jnl-notifications-wrapper\">\n    <a class=\"wd-jnl-email-alert\" href=\"https://myiopscience.iop.org/signin?origin=a0&return=https%3A%2F%2Fiopscience.iop.org%2Fmyiopscience%2Falerts%2Fsubscribe%3FarticleID%3D0004-637X%2F833%2F2%2F194\"><span\n            class=\"icon-alarm icon-alarm--jhp\"></span>Create citation alert</a>\n</div><!-- End Citation Alert Link -->\n                    </div>\n\t\t</div>\n    </div>\n    <!-- Article information ends -->\n<!-- Start Info top-->\n    <!-- end Info top --><div class=\"article-content\">\n\t<span id=\"articleId\" class=\"hide\">0004-637X/833/2/194</span>\n<!-- Start Abstract -->\n    <h2 id=\"artAbst\" class=\"collapse-blocked\">Abstract</h2>\n        <!-- Start article video abstract -->\n\t<!-- End article video abstract -->\n\t<div class=\"article-text wd-jnl-art-abstract cf\" itemprop=\"description\">\n             <P>With a large, unique spectroscopic survey in the fields of 28 galaxy-scale strong gravitational lenses, we identify groups of galaxies in the 26 adequately sampled fields. Using a group-finding algorithm, we find 210 groups with at least 5 member galaxies; the median number of members is 8. Our sample spans redshifts of 0.04\u00a0\u2264\u00a0<I>z</I> <SUB>grp</SUB>\u00a0\u2264\u00a00.76 with a median of 0.31, including 174 groups with 0.1\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<I>z</I> <SUB>grp</SUB>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.6. The groups have radial velocity dispersions of 60\u00a0\u2264\u00a0<I>\u03c3</I> <SUB>grp</SUB>\u00a0\u2264\u00a01200 km s<SUP>\u22121</SUP> with a median of 350 km s<SUP>\u22121</SUP>. We also discover a supergroup in field B0712+472 at <I>z</I> = 0.29 that consists of three main groups. We recover groups similar to ~85% of those previously reported in these fields within our redshift range of sensitivity and find 187 new groups with at least five members. The properties of our group catalog, specifically, (1) the distribution of <I>\u03c3</I> <SUB>grp</SUB>, (2) the fraction of all sample galaxies that are group members, and (3) the fraction of groups with significant substructure, are consistent with those for other catalogs. The distribution of group virial masses agrees well with theoretical expectations. Of the lens galaxies, 12 of 26 (46%) (B1422+231, B1600+434, B2114+022, FBQS J0951+2635, HE0435-1223, HST J14113+5211, MG0751+2716, MGJ1654+1346, PG 1115+080, Q ER 0047-2808, RXJ1131-1231, and WFI J2033-4723) are members of groups with at least five galaxies, and one more (B0712+472) belongs to an additional, visually identified group candidate. There are groups not associated with the lens that still are likely to affect the lens model; in six of 25 (24%) fields (excluding the supergroup), there is at least one massive (<I>\u03c3</I> <SUB>grp</SUB>\u00a0\u2265\u00a0500 km s<SUP>\u22121</SUP>) group or group candidate projected within 2' of the lens.</P> </div>\n    <!-- End abstract -->\n<!-- Start Export citation and abstract tools -->\n\t<p>\n\t\t<small>Export citation and abstract</small>\n\t\t<span class=\"btn-multi-block\">\n\t\t\t<a title=\"Export BibTex\">BibTeX</a>\n\t\t\t<a href=\"/export?articleId=0004-637X/833/2/194&doi=10.3847/1538-4357/833/2/194&exportFormat=iopexport_ris&exportType=abs&navsubmit=Export+abstract\" class=\"btn btn-primary wd-btn-cit-abs-ris\" title=\"Export RIS\">RIS</a>\n\t\t</span>\n\t</p>\n<!-- End Export citation and abstract tools -->\n<!-- Start AAS Related Links -->\n<div class=\"reveal-container reveal-closed reveal-plus-icon bdt-1 mt-2 mb-2 wd-jnl-art-article-aas-related-links\">\n  <div class=\"replica-h3 mt-0\">\n    <a href=\"#\" class=\"reveal-trigger\" data-reveal-label-alt=\"Hide related links\">Related links</a>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"reveal-content\">\n    <div class=\"article-meta\"> \n      <ul>\n      \t<li><a href=\"http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016ApJ...833..194W\" target=\"_blank\">NASA ADS Record <span class=\"icon-newtab\"></span></a></li>\n      \t<li><a href=\"http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/nph-objsearch?refcode=2016ApJ...833..194W&search_type=Search \" target=\"_blank\">NED Objects <span class=\"icon-newtab\"></span></a></li>\n      \t<li><a href=\"http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-ref?querymethod=bib&simbo=on&bibcode=2016ApJ...833..194W\" target=\"_blank\">Simbad Objects <span class=\"icon-newtab\"></span></a></li>\n      \t<li><a href=\"/journal/0004-637X/page/About%20Related%20Links\" target=\"_blank\">About Related Links</a></li>\n      \t</ul>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<!-- Start info bottom -->\n    <!-- End info bottom -->\n<!-- Start article full text -->\n\t<div xmlns:book=\"http://api.iop.org/Book/1.0/\" itemprop=\"articleBody\" class=\"wd-jnl-art-full-text article-text\">\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaa44e7s1\" name=\"apjaa44e7s1\">1.\u00a0INTRODUCTION</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>Gravitational lensing is an attractive method to measure cosmological parameters (e.g., Refsdal <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib60\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib60\">1964</a>; Oguri <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib57\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib57\">2007</a>; Suyu et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib65\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib65\">2013</a>), because the lensing phenomenon only depends on the geometry of the universe and the mass distribution along the line of sight. However, determining this mass can be difficult. Many of the properties of lens systems (e.g., shears or lensed image positions) are not well described by a model with only one galaxy contributing to the lensing potential, showing that groups or clusters of galaxies at the lens and even along the line of sight of the lens are important to the lensing (e.g., Keeton et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib35\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib35\">1997</a>; Lehar et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib40\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib40\">1997</a>; Keeton &amp; Zabludoff <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib36\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib36\">2004</a>; Wambsganss et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib71\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib71\">2005</a>; Jaroszynski &amp; Kostrzewa-Rutkowska <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib32\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib32\">2012</a>; Collett et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib15\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib15\">2013</a>).</p><p>Galaxy groups are interesting in addition to their possible impact on gravitational lensing because they are important to galaxy evolution. Groups are the most common environment for galaxies, with even our own Milky Way residing in the Local Group. Their lower velocity dispersions foster stronger galaxy\u2013galaxy interactions than do clusters (e.g., Zabludoff &amp; Mulchaey <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib79\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib79\">1998</a>). Moreover, cluster galaxy properties, such as mass or color, may first develop through \"pre-processing\" in the less dense group environment (e.g., Zabludoff et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib80\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib80\">1996</a>; Zabludoff &amp; Mulchaey <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib79\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib79\">1998</a>; McGee et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib49\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib49\">2009</a>; Just et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib33\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib33\">2015</a>).</p><p>To produce a new group sample with which to investigate the environments of lens systems and line-of-sight structures as well as the effect of environment on galaxy properties, we employ a spectroscopic survey in the fields of 28 galaxy-scale strong gravitational lenses (Momcheva et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib52\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib52\">2015</a>). In 26 of these fields, we construct a group-finding algorithm that works well for spectroscopic samples of variable completeness, field size, and sampling footprint, modifying the iterative method of Ammons et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib1\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib1\">2014</a>). Our method is also designed to find a range of group masses without favoring the most dynamically evolved systems (i.e., those with a significant quiescent galaxy population and/or detectable hot intracluster gas), unlike methods that use galaxy color, galaxy luminosity, or X-ray halo detections to identify groups or determine group properties. The resulting catalog includes groups ranging from very poor (<em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0~\u00a0100  km s<sup>\u22121</sup>) to rich clusters (~1000 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>) at 0.04\u00a0\u2264\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a00.76.</p><p>In this paper, we describe the data (Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s2\">2</a>), our group finding algorithm (Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s3\">3</a>), and its performance (Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s4\">4</a>). We present our group catalog and discuss its properties in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-1\">5.1</a>, describe a supergroup we identify in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-2\">5.2</a>, and comment on the lens environments and line-of-sight structures in Sections <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-3\">5.3</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-4\">5.4</a>, respectively. We suggest ways of using our catalog and group quality flags for various science cases in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s6\">6</a>.</p><p>Throughout this paper, we adopt the values of <em>H</em><sub>0</sub> = 71 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> Mpc<sup>\u22121</sup>, \u03a9<sub><em>m</em></sub> = 0.274, and \u03a9<sub>\u039b</sub> = 0.726 (Hinshaw et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib28\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib28\">2009</a>).</p></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaa44e7s2\" name=\"apjaa44e7s2\">2.\u00a0THE DATA</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s2-1\" name=\"apjaa44e7s2-1\">2.1.\u00a0Photometry</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>Images of each lens field were collected using the Mosaic-1 imager on the Kitt Peak National Observatory Mayall 4 m telescope and the Mosaic-2 imager on the Cerro Tololo Inter-American Observatory Blanco 4 m telescope. Williams et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib74\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib74\">2006</a>) detail these data and their reduction, which we summarize here. Each field was imaged using the \"nearly Mould\" <em>I</em>-band filter, as well as either the Harris <em>V</em> filter or the Harris <em>R</em> filter, depending on the redshift at which the 4000 \u00c5 break of the lens galaxy enters the <em>R</em> filter (<em>z</em>\u00a0\u2265\u00a00.35). Photometry was obtained using the routine MAG_AUTO of the SExtractor version 2.3.2 (Bertin &amp; Arnouts <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib8\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib8\">1996</a>). Galaxy colors were measured using aperture magnitudes after degrading one image to match the seeing of the other. The photometry was then calibrated to the Kron\u2013Cousins filter set using the imaging of the Landolt (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib39\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib39\">1992</a>) standard star fields. The photometry was used to select objects for spectroscopic follow-up and to calculate spectroscopic completeness.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s2-2\" name=\"apjaa44e7s2-2\">2.2.\u00a0Spectroscopy</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>The spectroscopic follow-up is described in Momcheva et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib52\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib52\">2015</a>). We summarize the most pertinent details here.</p><p>A sample of objects from the photometry was selected for spectroscopic follow-up using Hectospec on the MMT 6.5 m telescope and LDSS-2, LDSS-3, and IMACS on the Magellan\u00a06.5 m telescopes.</p><p>Priorities were ranked in the following manner. Objects identified as potential members of a red sequence (Williams et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib74\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib74\">2006</a>), regardless of whether that sequence is at the lens redshift, were given the highest priority. Objects outside potential red sequences, but redder than models of starburst galaxies at the lowest redshift candidate red sequence, bluer than members of the highest redshift candidate red sequence, and within 5' of the lens in each field were given second highest priority. Objects outside this color range, but within 5' of the lens were given third highest priority. Finally, objects farther than 5' from the lens were given the lowest priority. The limiting magnitude for spectroscopic targeting was either 20.5 or 21.5, depending on the instrument used.</p><p>This target selection method results in a strong radial gradient in the spectroscopic completeness. Some fields have patchy completeness because of the multislit mask designs. Furthermore, the spectroscopic completeness varies greatly from field to field; within 2' of the lens, completenesses range from ~20% to 90% (see Figures\u00a05, 36, and 37 in Momcheva et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib52\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib52\">2015</a>). Hectospec uses fibers with large holders that cannot be placed more closely on the sky than 20'', and the northern fields typically have fewer configurations. Thus, fields observed with this instrument have sparser but smoothly varying radial completeness over our full field of view. Those observed with LDSS-2, LDSS\u22123, and IMACS in many cases display a rectangular and/or patchy completeness that is inconsistent with the total available aperture of the instrument (see Figure Set <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f7\">7</a>, e.g., fields b1422 and q1017). These distributions were due to the mask designs. Early LDSS-2 masks were all centered on the lens, resulting in higher completeness within 5' from the lens. Later observations were planned assuming a five-mask configuration tiled in the shape of the pips on the \"five side\" of a die, with one mask in the middle and four masks that slightly overlapped each other arranged in a square. The sampled field of view generally extends to at least 1<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> for groups with velocity dispersions of up to ~500 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> at <em>z</em>\u00a0<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/gsim.gif\" alt=\"gsim\" align=\"baseline\" />\u00a00.1 and for richer clusters with velocity dispersions of up to ~900 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> at <em>z</em>\u00a0<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/gsim.gif\" alt=\"gsim\" align=\"baseline\" />\u00a00.2.</p><p>Four fields (he0435, q0047, q0158, and rxj1131) were imaged while one of the eight CCDs in the Mosaic-2 camera was non-operational in late 2003. This resulted in a dearth of imaging data over a ~9'\u00a0<b>&#x00d7;</b>\u00a018' region in the eastern portion of each field. Since the spectroscopic targets were selected from our photometry, these regions have no spectroscopic coverage.</p><p>For 2 of the 28 fields, b1608 and pmn2004, the spectroscopic completenesses are very low because of the limited spectroscopic observations. Thus, we do not include these fields in our group catalog.</p><p>Redshifts were calculated with a routine based on that of Cool et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib16\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib16\">2008</a>), which involves a <em>\u03c7</em><sup>2</sup> fit of the measured spectra to templates. The resulting redshifts of objects observed with IMACS and LDSS-3 were checked visually against the sky-subtracted, two-dimensional spectra. The median uncertainty on the redshifts is ~0.0002, or ~60 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> at <em>z</em> = 0.3.</p><p>Additional objects with published redshifts taken from NED<sup xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"fnref\"><a class=\"fnref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7fn11\">6</a></sup>\n were included as well. In two fields, the NED additions were significant. There were 240 NED additions to h12531, as it includes a previously studied supercluster at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a01.237 (Demarco et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib17\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib17\">2007</a>), and 133 to pg1115, which includes the <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.485 cluster RXJ1117.4+0743. These additions are visible in the sky plots as small densely sampled regions near the edges of our fields.</p><p>We note that our algorithm (see Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s3-1\">3.1</a> and Appendix <xref summary=\" and Appendix A) is not optimized f\">A</xref>) is not optimized for the relatively overdense patches arising from adding many NED redshifts in the fields h12531 and pg1115. Before running the group algorithm, we therefore discarded the galaxies obtained from NED in these two fields that have I-band magnitudes fainter than 21.5 mag (165 galaxies in field 12531 and 21 galaxies in field pg1115) to make the magnitude limits of those fields better comparable to the rest of our survey. In h12531, this cut removes many galaxies at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a01.24. Since our work is optimized at <em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a01, we refer to Demarco et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib17\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib17\">2007</a>) and Tanaka et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib67\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib67\">2009</a>) for further details.</p><p>In field sbs1520, the lens galaxy has two contradictory redshifts available in the literature: <em>z</em> = 0.72 from Chavushyan et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib14\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib14\">1997</a>) and <em>z</em> = 0.761 from Auger et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib4\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib4\">2008</a>). Thus, neither one appears in our redshift catalog, although both are marked in plots when relevant.</p><p>The final redshift catalog includes 9662 unique galaxies. This catalog includes 9370 galaxies that are not in the preliminary catalog and analysis presented in Momcheva et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib51\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib51\">2006</a>), most of which are in 20 additional fields.</p><p>To determine the redshift interval over which each field is most sensitive, we consider the spectroscopic field size and how the spectroscopic completeness varies over our I-band magnitude range. We assume a homogeneous universe, use the luminosity functions of Faber et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib20\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib20\">2007</a>) for 0\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a01, and implement K-corrections using an LRG spectral template, as in Ammons et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib1\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib1\">2014</a>). Although the selection functions vary slightly from field to field, the peak is at z\u00a0~\u00a00.2\u20130.25, with generally high sensitivity from 0.05\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5. The survey sensitivity decreases at <em>z</em>\u00a0<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/gsim.gif\" alt=\"gsim\" align=\"baseline\" />\u00a00.5; so, it is more difficult for us to identify structures at these higher redshifts.</p></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaa44e7s3\" name=\"apjaa44e7s3\">3.\u00a0FINDING GROUPS</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>Several group and cluster identification methods exist in the literature. Massive dynamically evolved low-redshift structures can be readily detected in X-ray observations (e.g., Lloyd-Davies et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib42\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib42\">2011</a>), as can clusters at all redshifts via the Sunyaev\u2013Zeldovich effect (e.g., Bleem et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib10\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib10\">2015</a>; Planck Collaboration et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib58\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib58\">2015</a>). However, these methods also require some member galaxy redshifts to determine the structure's redshift.</p><p>Other group finders rely on additional sources of data, such as photometry and/or photometric redshifts, to locate groups using adaptive matched filters (e.g., Szabo et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib66\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib66\">2011</a>), red-sequence identification (e.g., Williams et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib74\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib74\">2006</a>; Koester et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib38\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib38\">2007</a>), or low surface brightness enhancement identification (e.g., Gonzalez et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib26\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib26\">2001</a>; White et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib73\">2005</a>). These methods can be useful, especially when the spectroscopic data are sparse compared with the amount of photometric information available, but are typically more sensitive to massive evolved systems.</p><p>Since even low-mass groups can affect gravitational lensing models, we require a method that is sensitive to less massive systems as well as clusters. One such approach is to compile large spectroscopic samples and then search for spatial and redshift clustering. The friends-of-friends (Huchra &amp; Geller <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib31\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib31\">1982</a>) and the Voronoi-Delaunay (Marinoni et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib44\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib44\">2002</a>) methods are commonly used. These techniques can be useful for uniformly complete redshift samples, but cannot be used for samples with large spatial variations in spectroscopic completeness, which we have; in this situation, iterative methods, such as that of Wilman et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib75\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib75\">2005</a>), are more appropriate.</p><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s3-1\" name=\"apjaa44e7s3-1\">3.1.\u00a0Algorithm</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We use the iterative approach of Ammons et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib1\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib1\">2014</a>) after modification to accommodate our spectroscopic sample and to find less massive structures. We develop a two-phase process where we identify candidate density peaks based on galaxy overdensities in velocity and spatial projection and then iterate for the galaxy membership and group properties. The main differences between our method and that of Ammons et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib1\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib1\">2014</a>) are the method of generating candidate density peaks, the projected spatial criteria in the membership iteration, and the parameter values we choose. We automate the peak-finding process. We do not use any magnitude or color information to identify candidate groups, because we wish to be able to find lower mass groups without prominent red sequences as well as rich clusters. The resulting group catalog is produced algorithmically, with parameter choices justified in this section and in Appendix <xref summary=\"ion and in Appendix A; only one system, a\">A</xref>; only one system, a complex supergroup, is altered after the fact (see Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-2\">5.2</a>). Our algorithm is tuned to select groups that we visually identify, but applies criteria uniformly so that our resulting group catalog is reproducible. It also finds some groups with similar properties that were not visually identified.</p><p>There are nine parameters in our method of selecting candidate peaks and determining group membership, some of which are degenerate, leading to multiple ways to achieve roughly the same ends. We require our catalog to include most of the likely structures we identify by eye as obvious overdensities of galaxies in velocity and projected spatial position (see Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s3-2\">3.2</a>). We also aim to minimize the number of structures with unphysically large velocity dispersions. Although there is some variation in the exact group catalog, most of the groups are stable to small changes in the parameters. We test the \"realness\" of our groups in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s4\">4</a>.</p><p>The steps of our algorithm are as follows:</p><ul class=\"clear-list wd-inline-list\"><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">1.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\">We identify overdensities of galaxies in velocity by binning the galaxies in 1200 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> wide bins (three times the velocity dispersion of that of typical groups we expect). This method relies on the uncertainties in redshift, and consequently velocity, being small compared to the velocity bin width, as is the case for our sample, so that galaxies can be robustly binned. We use the same bin width for all redshifts, although this velocity interval will correspond to a varying rest frame velocity dispersion. We select velocity bins with at least five galaxies. We then shift the velocity bins five times by steps of 200 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>, half the expected velocity dispersion for a typical group in our sample, and again select the velocity bins with at least five galaxies. These multiple velocity bin positions reduce the chance of a group being missed because its members were split by a velocity bin boundary and increases the chance for groups to be well centered in a velocity bin. We do not use a spatial selection in this step, but do so in the next step below.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">2.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\">We look for spatial overdensities of the galaxies within these velocity bins.We divide the observed field into grid squares 3.3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> on a side, assuming a group-like velocity dispersion of 400 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> and using the formula for <em>r</em><sub>200</sub> given by Carlberg et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib11\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib11\">1997</a>) as an approximation of the virial radius:<div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaa44e7eqn1\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7eqn1.gif\" alt=\"Equation (1)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&{r}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }\\approx {r}_{200}=\\displaystyle \\frac{\\sqrt{3}{\\sigma }_{\\mathrm{grp}}}{10H(z)},\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t1\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div>where<div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaa44e7eqn2\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7eqn2.gif\" alt=\"Equation (2)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&H(z)={H}_{0}\\sqrt{{{\\rm{\\Omega }}}_{m}{(1+{z}_{\\mathrm{gal}})}^{3}+{{\\rm{\\Omega }}}_{{\\rm{\\Lambda }}}}\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t2\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div>for a flat cosmology, and <em>z</em><sub>gal</sub> corresponds to the lower boundary of the velocity bin. We center the grid on the median R.A. and decl. of the galaxies in each bin. We do not treat the lens galaxy as special in this or in any other step of the group finder. We define each grid square with five or more galaxies as a \"candidate peak\" and calculate its median redshift, R.A., and decl. We use these quantities as starting points for our iterative group member identification. We repeat this candidate peak finder nine more times, centering the grid in different positions (shifting it a quarter of a grid square in R.A., a quarter of a grid square in decl., and a quarter of a grid square in both R.A. and decl.). These multiple positions increase the likelihood of identifying multiple overdensities of galaxies in a single velocity bin as candidate peaks if one (or more) is split by a grid square boundary for one grid position and increases the likelihood of groups being well-centered in at least one grid position. We use all the candidate peaks generated in all of these grid positions for all of these velocity bin phases, even though some are different parts of the same structures. The combination of velocity bin width, grid square size, velocity dispersion, and number of galaxies per bin or grid square is chosen so the resulting group catalog best reproduces our initial visual identifications discussed in the next section.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">3.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\">We optimize the group membership using these candidate peaks as starting points. We select galaxies within a redshift interval \u0394<em>z</em> of the candidate peak redshift and 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> from the peak's projected spatial centroid assuming a velocity dispersion of 400 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>. We choose a \u0394<em>z</em> that corresponds to 6600 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> at the candidate peak's redshift, which corresponds to \u00b1 three times the velocity dispersion of a Coma-sized cluster. We select a large \u0394<em>z</em> compared with our initially assumed velocity dispersion to avoid excluding galaxies in the high-velocity tails should the identified peak correspond to a higher velocity dispersion structure, as would become evident during the membership optimization process described below. Using these galaxies, we calculate the biweight redshift (<em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>), mean position, and the cosmologically corrected biweight line-of-sight velocity dispersion (<em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>). We then select the galaxies within 3<em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub> of this new mean redshift after transforming the velocity dispersion to a redshift interval using<div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaa44e7eqn3\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7eqn3.gif\" alt=\"Equation (3)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&{\\rm{\\Delta }}z=\\displaystyle \\frac{3{\\sigma }_{\\mathrm{grp}}}{c},\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t3\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div>and within 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>, using <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>, of the spatial centroid.In the first iteration, we also reject members that are more than a velocity dispersion away from their nearest neighbor in velocity, as they are unlikely to be members. This choice has an effect on roughly 20% of the catalog, generally one or more galaxies being removed in the outskirts of the group as projected on the sky; the new group redshift and/or velocity dispersion differs by more than three times the error in <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub> or <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>, respectively, for ~1% of the groups. There are an additional 19 groups with at least 5 members when clipping is not performed, but a structure with an unlikely large velocity dispersion is also identified. Thus, we choose to perform this clipping to reduce the identification of galaxies as group members that are in the tails of both the group velocity and spatial distributions and minimize unrealistically large structures.Using the galaxies that satisfy these cuts in velocity and position, we recalculate the mean redshift and spatial centroid and find the resulting membership. We recalculate the group parameters and redetermine the galaxies within 3<em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub> of the mean redshift and 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> of the spatial centroid for 10 total iterations. We consider a group to have converged if the membership does not change in the last 3 iterations. Given our field boundaries, groups at low redshift and/or with large velocity dispersions may be sampled to less than 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>. We flag any group not sampled to at least 1<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> in the catalog tables (Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t2\">2</a>, and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t4\">4</a>).<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\"> </a>\n<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t2\"> </a>\n</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">4.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\">Large structures may have member galaxies spread over a projected area larger than 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> when a velocity dispersion of 400 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> is assumed, therefore our binning and gridding systems might generate multiple candidate peaks for a single structure. Because our iterative procedure can find the true larger group, these multiple candidate peaks may converge on identical or overlapping groups. Thus, we must remove duplicate groups and combine nearly identical groups (see Appendix <xref summary=\"roups (see Appendix A for details). If mu\">A</xref> for details). If multiple candidate peaks converge on multiple identical group memberships, we select one of the identical groups without rerunning the algorithm. If in more than 75% of the trials a group converges with the same membership, we add that group to our catalog. In other cases, where a group shares at least 50% of its members with another, we determine the mean of these groups' spatial centroids, redshifts, velocity dispersions, and virial radii, and reiterate on the membership to produce a single group for the catalog. If between 0% and 50% of a group's members are also assigned to another group, we determine to which group the galaxies are more likely to be bound and remove them from the other (see Appendix <xref summary=\"other (see Appendix A.3).\">A.3</xref>).</div></li></ul><p>\n</p><div tabindex=\"-1\" id=\"apjaa44e7t1\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\"><p><b>Table name=\"apjaa44e7fn1\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn1\"></a><sup> a</sup>A lens group.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn2\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn2\"></a><sup> b</sup>Projected distance between the lens and the group centroid.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn3\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn3\"></a><sup> c</sup>Masses are reported when \u226510<sup>13</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub>.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn4\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn4\"></a><sup> d</sup>(1) <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.1 (groups at lower redshift are most likely not sampled out to <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> because of the spectroscopic field size); (2) <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> intersects the edge of the well-sampled region of the field because the group is large and/or at low <em>z</em>; (3) <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> extends beyond the well-sampled region of the field because the group centroid or several of its members are near the edge of the field; (4) group membership was adjusted manually to remedy overlapping membership.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn5\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn5\"></a><sup> e</sup>Groups in the literature that have a redshift within 3<em>\u03c3</em><sub><em>z</em></sub> of a group in our catalog. type=\"math/tex\">{}_{-0.0070}^{+0.0070}</script></span></span>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"char\" char=\".\">10.74</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"right\">250<span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\"
