char=\".\">3</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table><p><small>\n<p><strong>Notes.</strong></p>\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn14\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn14\"></a><sup> a</sup>A lens group.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn15\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn15\"></a><sup> b</sup>Numbering is not continued from Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t2\">2</a>.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn16\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn16\"></a><sup> c</sup>Uncertainties are not calculated for <em>N</em><sub><em>m</em></sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a04\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn17\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn17\"></a><sup> d</sup>Projected distance between the lens and the group centroid.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn18\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn18\"></a><sup> e</sup>(1) <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.1 (groups at lower redshift are most likely not sampled out to <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> because of the spectroscopic field size); (2) <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> intersects the edge of the well-sampled region of the field because the group is large and/or at low <em>z</em>; (3) <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> extends beyond the well-sampled region of the field because the group centroid or several of its members are located near the edge of the field; (4) group membership was adjusted manually to remedy overlapping membership.\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-ascii\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7t4_ascii.txt?doi=10.3847/1538-4357/833/2/194\" target=\"_blank\">ASCII</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7t4_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">Typeset image</a></span></p></div><p>We compare our group catalog to several group and cluster catalogs from the literature: CNOC2 (Carlberg et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib12\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib12\">2001</a>), EDisCS (White et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib73\">2005</a>), GAMA (Robotham et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib61\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib61\">2011</a>), zCOSMOS (Knobel et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib37\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib37\">2012</a>), and a flux-limited group catalog for SDSS galaxies (Tempel et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib68\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib68\">2014</a>) (see Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f6\">6</a>). While our catalog is similar to others in size, limiting magnitude, group velocity dispersions, and group redshifts, it is unique in that it is in fields of galaxy-scale strong gravitational lenses.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaa44e7f6\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaa44e7f6\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f6_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 6.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 6.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f6_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 6.</strong>\u00a0Comparison of our algorithmic group catalog (red stars) to others, including CNOC2 (green circles), EDisCS (orange), GAMA (cyan), zCOSMOS (blue), and an SDSS flux-limited catalog (magenta). Here we include only groups with \u2265 five spectroscopic members and a reported velocity dispersion. Left: approximate limiting magnitudes for the redshift surveys used for each catalog transformed to <em>I</em><sub>Vega</sub> and the number of groups found. The red star represents our fainter limiting magnitude, which was used for the majority of the survey (Momcheva et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib52\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib52\">2015</a>). Right: median velocity dispersions vs. redshifts for these group catalogs. Bars represent the total range in group properties. Our catalog has a number of groups for its limiting magnitude, redshift range, and velocity dispersion range comparable to the zCOSMOS group catalog. The uniqueness of our catalog is that it targets the fields of strong gravitational lensing galaxies.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaa44e7f6\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f6\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaa44e7f6\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f6\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure></div><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s5-2\" name=\"apjaa44e7s5-2\">5.2.\u00a0Supergroup</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>In field b0712 our algorithm identifies a structure at <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub> = 0.2941 with the largest membership found in our sample (230 galaxies). However, it exhibits three clumps in projected spatial position and two distinct velocity peaks. While having clumps in space and velocity in clusters is reasonable if groups have fallen in, but have not completely virialized within the cluster, these clumps have projected spatial centroids that are several Mpc apart, on the order of or larger than the cluster virial radius. We therefore conclude that this structure is a supergroup, remove it from our final group catalog, and present its properties and those of its three main substructures in Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t3\">3</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t6\">6</a> and in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f5\">5</a>.</p><p>Versions of this structure have been identified before. Fassnacht &amp; Lubin (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib21\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib21\">2002</a>) find a much smaller group (ten members with <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub> = 306 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>) at <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub> = 0.2909 with their smaller sample (~50 redshifts within several arcminutes of the lens). Momcheva (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib53\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib53\">2009</a>), using an earlier version of the redshift catalog we use, finds a large cluster (231 galaxies), but suggests it might either be a sheet of galaxies or several groups that are merging, similar to our interpretation.</p><p>In a different field, Smit et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib62\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib62\">2015</a>) find a supergroup with similar properties to ours. Their super galaxy group at <em>z</em> = 0.37 has four component groups. The difference in group average velocity between the lowest and highest redshift components is about twice as large as the difference between ours, although when their outlying component is excluded, the velocity difference between the remaining lowest and highest redshift components is roughly five times smaller than ours. The projected spatial separations of their components are similar to our separation (a few Mpc). The component velocity dispersions are similar: ours range from 330 to 420 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> and theirs from 303 to 580 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>. However, our components have more identified members (39 to 54 galaxies compared to their 13 to 29). Our spectroscopic completeness over most of our field is comparable to theirs (as suggested by Gonzalez et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib25\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib25\">2005</a>), although they have a much deeper limiting magnitude (<em>R</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a022.5), which means that our components are probably richer structures than theirs.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s5-3\" name=\"apjaa44e7s5-3\">5.3.\u00a0Lens Galaxy Environments</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We find 12 of the 26 lens galaxies in our sample (46%) to be members of groups with at least 5 galaxies. These lenses are b1422, b1600, b2114, fbq0951, he0435, hst14113, mg0751, mg1654, pg1115, q0047, rxj1131, and wfi2033 (see Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a> for group properties). One additional lens, b0712, is identified as a member of a non-algorithmic candidate group (see Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t4\">4</a>). While there are 2 non-algorithmic candidate groups near the lens redshift in field bri0952, the lens galaxy is not a member. Our percentage of lenses in groups with at least 5 galaxies agrees well with the 42% found by Momcheva (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib53\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib53\">2009</a>), who used redshifts drawn from an earlier version of Momcheva et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib52\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib52\">2015</a>).</p><p>The remaining 13 lenses are not identified as group members but are most likely not isolated. Of these 9 lenses with firm spectroscopic redshifts, 5 have at least 5 other galaxies in the same redshift bin in Figure Set <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f4\">4</a>. Four (bri0952, he2149, mg1131, and q1355) are not in overdensities of galaxies, although 3 are at <em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a00.5, where our redshift sample is much less sensitive. Because of the ambiguity of the lens redshift in field sbs1520, we cannot conclude whether it is located in a group, but we do find galaxies near both possible redshifts. The remaining 3 lenses (h1413, h12531, and q1017) have only photometric redshifts, and they are not located in peaks of galaxies in the redshift number distribution.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s5-4\" name=\"apjaa44e7s5-4\">5.4.\u00a0Significant Line-of-sight Structures in Lens Fields</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>The importance of a line-of-sight structure to the lensing potential is affected by the structure mass and its proximity to the lens both in redshift and projected on the sky (Wong et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib77\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib77\">2011</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib76\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib76\">2012</a>; McCully et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib48\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib48\">2016</a>). We select groups and candidate groups within 2' of the lens, as Wong et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib77\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib77\">2011</a>) found that most line-of-sight shear was caused by objects within this distance, and we select a high-mass threshold of <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0\u2265\u00a0500 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> to estimate how often line-of-sight structure might be important when determining the lensing potential. We do not include field b0712 because of the ambiguity that the supergroup provides; if this structure is one monolithic structure, it is very likely significant for the lensing, but if the three main substructures are better tracers of the mass, they are not as significant. For this analysis we therefore use a sample of 25 fields.</p><p>All but two of the systems for which a source redshift estimate is available have <em>z</em><sub>source</sub>\u00a0&gt;\u00a01. This means that our group catalog is not sensitive to all mass between the observer and the source for most of these fields. French et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib22\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib22\">2014</a>) find that their beams that most effectively lens <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a010 sources generally have significant halos with 0.1\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.6 (single-halo beams) or 0.3\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a01.0 (multi-halo beams). In addition, the mass between the main lens and the observer typically affects the lensing potential more than those between the main lens and the source (McCully et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib47\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib47\">2014</a>). Since all our lens galaxies lie between <em>z</em> = 0.1 and 0.9, we are probably sensitive to the redshift range over which single groups might significantly affect the lensing potential as well as most of the redshift range for which multiple line-of-sight masses could be important.</p><p>In at least six of our 25 (24%) fields, there is at least one group or candidate group of which the lens is not a member that is likely to significantly affect the lensing potential. In future work, we will further quantify the importance of lens environments and and line-of-sight structures to the lensing models of these fields.</p></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaa44e7s6\" name=\"apjaa44e7s6\">6.\u00a0USING OUR GROUP CATALOG</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>While we make choices in our group-finding algorithm to balance completeness and contamination, we provide several tables and quality flags so that a user can tailor the group catalog for a particular science case. Here we give some suggestions of how to select subsamples of our catalog for various purposes.</p><p>Some of the groups in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a> have member galaxies quite close to the edge of their fields, and thus they might have group properties (primarily the projected spatial centroid) that are not well determined. Moreover, some are at redshifts such that they are not sampled out to at least <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>. Therefore, to obtain the group sample with the highest confidence and the best-determined group properties, we suggest to use only groups in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a> with no flag (column 11). Such a subset would be well suited to studies of environmental effects on galaxy properties for which contamination is to be minimized. Additionally, when the poorest groups can be excluded in order to remove those most likely to be spurious, groups with <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a0200 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> could also be removed.</p><p>For lensing analyses of these fields, we suggest using all the information in Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t4\">4</a>. We note that this choice will include groups at low redshift that we might not sample out to a virial radius or groups near the edge of our field with likely poorly determined spatial centroids.</p><p>To prioritize additional spectroscopic follow-up in these fields and thus to select galaxies that are likely to be at redshifts near our candidate groups, we recommend Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t2\">2</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t4\">4</a>. When the intention is to expand the footprint on the sky and thus interest is in groups that are detected on the edge of our observed fields or for which we do not sample out to at least <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>, galaxies from Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a> with flags of 1, 2, or 3 could also be included.</p><p>Users who wish to know of anything in these fields that could even possibly be a structure should use everything in Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t2\">2</a>, and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t4\">4</a> as well as either the first line (when the overall supergroup of b0712 is preferred) or the second through fourth lines (if the supergroup's main substructures are of interest) in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t3\">3</a>. We note, however, that the resulting composite will include groups that are identified in different ways.</p></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaa44e7s7\" name=\"apjaa44e7s7\">7.\u00a0CONCLUSIONS</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>We create a group catalog for 26 of the 28 gravitational lens fields in Momcheva et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib52\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib52\">2015</a>). This catalog improves the characterization of the environments of the gravitational lenses and of line-of-sight groups and clusters in these fields, which will constrain how much such structures affect the lensing potentials.</p><p>We develop an iterative group finder for redshift samples with variable spectroscopic completeness levels and sampling footprints. We find 210 groups with at least 5 member galaxies in these fields. We newly identify 187 groups. These groups span 0.04\u00a0\u2264\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a00.76 with our range of greatest sensitivity at 0.2\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5 and a median of 0.31. Our groups have a velocity dispersion range of 60\u20131200 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> with most between 100 and 600 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> and a median of 350 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>. Our groups have from 5 to 66 members with a median of 8.</p><p>We test our group finder by comparing our group catalog to those in the same fields in the literature. We find groups similar to most (~85%) that were previously reported within our redshift range of sensitivity.</p><p>We also compare our groups' distribution of <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>, distribution of <em>M</em><sub>vir</sub>, incidence of substructure, and fraction of all sample galaxies that are group members to the literature. Our catalog agrees well with the empirical and theoretical expectations.</p><p>Our main results are as follows:</p><ul>\n<li>We identify a supergroup in field b0712 with <em>z</em> = 0.29. This structure has three main components with 39 to 54 members and <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub> from 330 to 420 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> that occupy different regions projected on the sky and in radial velocity.</li>\n<li>Of the 26 lenses in our sample for which we produce group catalogs, 12 (46%) are members of \u22655 member groups (b1422, b1600, b2114, fbq0951, he0435, hst14113, mg0751, mg1654, pg1115, q0047, rxj1131, and wfi2033), and 1 (b0712) is identified as a member of an additional visually identified group candidate. These structures, which have <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub> from 110 to 800 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>, are likely to affect lensing models.</li>\n<li>In 6 of 25 (24%) of these fields that do not have the supergroup, there is at least one group or candidate group that does not include the lens galaxy with <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0\u2265\u00a0500 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> projected within 2' of the lens, which likely affects the lensing potential.</li>\n</ul><p>\n</p><p>Further analysis of the environments and line-of-sight structures of these lens fields will be discussed in a forthcoming paper.</p></div> <div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>We thank the anonymous referee for helpful comments. We also thank Dan Marrone, George Rieke, Dennis Zaritsky, and K. Decker French for helpful discussions. M.L.W. and A.I.Z. acknowledge support from NASA grants ADP-NNX10AD476 and ADP-NNX10AE88G, as well as NSF grant AST-0908280. M.L.W. also thanks the Technology and Research Initiative Fund (TRIF) Imaging Fellowship program for its support. S.M.A. thanks NASA through Hubble Fellowship grant <em>HST</em>-HF-51250.01-A from the Space Telescope Science Institute, which is operated by the Association of Universities for Research in Astronomy, Incorporated under NASA contract NAS5-26555. Portions of this work were performed under the auspices of the U.S. Department of Energy by Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory under Contract DE-AC52-07NA27344. C.R.K. acknowledges support from NSF grant AST-1211385.</p><p><em>Facilities:</em> Mayall (Mosaic-I) - ,  Blanco (Mosaic-II) - ,  <em>Magellan</em>-1 (LDSS-2 - ,  LDSS-3) - ,  <em>Magellan</em>-2 (IMACS) - ,  MMT (Hectospec). - \n</p></div><h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaa44e7app1\" name=\"apjaa44e7app1\">APPENDIX A: CHOOSING PARAMETERS FOR OUR ALGORITHM</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>Here we describe the main parameters of our group-finding algorithm and how we choose them.</p><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7app1-1\" name=\"apjaa44e7app1-1\">A.1.\u00a0Candidate Peak Selection</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>There are several degenerate parameters that affect what types of groups can be identified as candidate peaks. The width of the bins in the galaxy velocity distribution affects how easily groups projected along the same line of sight can be distinguished. The grid square width in the galaxy sky position likewise affects how easily groups with similar radial velocities but different locations projected on the sky can be identified as separate candidate peaks. If velocity bins or grid squares are too small, large and/or sparsely sampled structures (i.e., clusters and higher redshift structures) will be artificially fragmented and might not be identified as candidate peaks. If the bins or grid squares are too large, multiple structures might be identified as a single candidate peak. This conflation can also result in no group being identified if the average position and velocity of the galaxies are in sparsely populated regions. For both the velocity bins and sky grid, we need to decide how many galaxies must be in a bin or grid square to further consider that it might contain a group. If the threshold is set too high, we will only ever be able to find the richest structures. If it is set too low, we have a larger chance of including spurious groups in our sample.</p><p>Because we define the grid square sizes in terms of <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>, where we use the relation for <em>r</em><sub>200</sub> given by Carlberg et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib11\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib11\">1997</a>):</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaa44e7eqn5\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7eqn5.gif\" alt=\"Equation (5)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&{r}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }\\approx {r}_{200}=\\displaystyle \\frac{\\sqrt{3}{\\sigma }_{\\mathrm{grp}}}{10H(z)},\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t5\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>the initial velocity dispersion guess affects the properties above.</p><p>How the grid is centered is another choice. We place the center of a grid square at the median R.A. and decl. of the galaxies in each velocity bin to increase the likelihood that the best-populated structure in each velocity bin is centered in a grid square. However, the projected spatial distributions of galaxies in a given velocity bin are often complex, with multiple overdensities and/or a concentration plus a large diffuse component. Thus, we shift the grid to nine other positions (in units of a quarter of the width of a grid square in R.A., decl., and both) to increase the likelihood that multiple overdensities, where present, are centered in a grid square in at least one of the grid positions. Mismatches between galaxy overdensities and grid squares would primarily impact groups with few members in our redshift catalog and/or with members spread out on the sky; groups with up to eight members could be missed if they have their members split equally between two grid squares for all grid positions. If an overdensity is identified as a candidate peak but is not well centered in a grid square, then our subsequent iterative membership procedure can remedy this, as the projected spatial centroid is allowed to vary.</p><p>We test our method using velocity bins of 1000, 1200, 1500, 1600, and 2000 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> and several grid square widths from 1.5<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> to 5<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>. We set the galaxy number threshold at three and five galaxies for the velocity bins and three, four, and five galaxies for the spatial grid squares. We test using velocity dispersion initial guesses of 300, 400, and 500 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>. Velocity bins of 1200 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> width, grid squares of 3.3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> width, galaxy thresholds of five galaxies for both velocity bins and grid squares, an initial guess of the velocity dispersion of 400 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>, and multiple grid positions are good parameters to distinguish multiple visually identified groups and avoid creating a large number of small most likely spurious groups or unphysically massive structures. While the majority of the catalog is robust for a grid square size within the range of 3\u20133.6 <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> (tested in steps of 0.1 <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>), we select the value that maximizes the number of recovered visually identified groups while minimizing the number of unphysically large structures.</p><p>Most of our groups have small velocity dispersions, with a peak in the number distribution at ~300 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> (median value of 350 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> for groups with at least five members) and a tail to higher values (see Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f3\">3</a>). To test how our assumption of 400 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> for the initial velocity dispersion affects the final <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub> distribution, we compare the results from our three velocity dispersion initial guesses. Overall, the catalogs are similar; the majority of groups have similar or identical calculated group properties. However, the 300 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> catalog finds fewer groups, including 24 fewer visually identified groups. The 500 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> catalog finds double the number of groups with <em>M</em><sub>vir</sub>\u00a0\u2265\u00a010<sup>15</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub>, including one with an unphysical <em>M</em><sub>vir</sub>\u00a0=\u00a05.6\u00a0<b>&#x00d7;</b>\u00a010<sup>15</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub> (<em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0=\u00a01990 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>). The 400 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> catalog agrees best with the velocity dispersion distribution from zCOSMOS, although none of these catalogs have distributions distinguishable from it using a K-S test. The 300 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> catalog suffers from incompleteness when compared to the MXXL mass function at slightly higher masses than the 400 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> catalog. The high mass slope of the 500 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> catalog does not agree as well with that of MXXL due to its larger number of unphysically massive structures. Thus, we choose to use an initial velocity dispersion of 400 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7app1-2\" name=\"apjaa44e7app1-2\">A.2.\u00a0Group Membership Iteration</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We must select a redshift range \u0394<em>z</em> within which to look for possible group members. If \u0394<em>z</em> is too small, the velocity tails of massive structures get clipped, but if it is too large, large-scale structure might be misidentified as a group or cluster. We select \u0394<em>z</em> equivalent to 6600 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> at the candidate peak redshift (using the special relativistic velocities) to include galaxies up to 3<em>\u03c3</em> from the mean velocity for a cluster with a velocity dispersion of 1100 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>, that of a Coma-like cluster. Very rare structures with even larger velocity dispersions can still be found by our algorithm, but their high-velocity tails will be somewhat clipped. Some small groups near larger structures in redshift also may be clipped. Even though most of our groups can be found using a smaller \u0394<em>z</em>, choosing 6600 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> ensures that we properly sample the few massive clusters in our fields, so that their velocity dispersions and contributions to the lensing potentials are not underestimated.</p><p>In the first step of the group membership iteration, we must assume a velocity interval and a radius within which to consider possible group galaxies. We assume a velocity dispersion of 400 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> and the virial radius relation given above for the same reasons given in the previous section.</p><p>For the final group catalog, we include galaxies projected up to 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> from the group center on the sky. Including group members out to 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> will likely increase the contamination by nonmembers, but it improves both our group and group member completeness. Both Carlberg et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib12\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib12\">2001</a>) and Wilman et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib75\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib75\">2005</a>) accept members out to 1.5<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>. The cosmological hydrodynamical simulations of Bah\u00e9 et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib5\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib5\">2013</a>) show that while beyond 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> almost all galaxies are infalling into the host halos for the first time, some galaxies now at ~3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> passed within ~1<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> earlier and thus have been influenced by the host halo.</p><p>We require the velocity dispersion to be at least 50 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> for the structure to be considered a halo.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7app1-3\" name=\"apjaa44e7app1-3\">A.3.\u00a0Duplicate Removal</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We determine which groups include galaxies assigned to more than one group (overlapping members) in multiple trials. When at least 75% of the trials converge on an identical group, we add that group to our catalog. When a group is only found once among all the trials, it is discarded, because it is unlikely to be real. Any group that shares more than 50% of its membership with a group with at least twice as many members is discarded, which prevents the artificial fragmentation of rich clusters. In other cases where a given group shares at least 50% of its members with another, we determine the mean group spatial centroid, the mean group redshift, the maximum group velocity dispersion, and the maximum group virial radius and reiterate on the group membership to produce the final group for the catalog.</p><p>The main parameters here are the percentage of group membership overlap and the fraction of groups found for a given candidate peak that must be identical to accept this group as is.</p><p>If the percentage of group membership overlap is set too high, then many galaxies are assigned to multiple groups. If it is set too low, we will combine groups that have most of their galaxies well separated, but have some outliers that overlap, which results in only one or neither group remaining in our catalog.</p><p>As most of the groups found among multiple trials either have identical membership or do not overlap at all, our catalog is fairly insensitive to our choice of group membership overlap fraction. Out of 53652 group membership overlap comparisons, only 238 (0.4%) have overlap fractions between 5% and 75%.</p><p>We rerun our membership iteration on those groups that have at least 50% overlapping membership with another group. Of these, 47 of 50 converge into 47 new groups. We remove the remaining 3.</p><p>After the second run of the membership iterator, there are seven pairs of groups that share a few member assignments (one galaxy in two cases, two galaxies in three cases, and three galaxies in two cases). To determine to which group these remaining galaxies belong, we calculate the offset in velocity and projected spatial position of each shared galaxy from its two possible groups using</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaa44e7eqn6\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7eqn6.gif\" alt=\"Equation (6)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&{R}^{2}={({v}_{{gxy}}-{v}_{\\mathrm{grp}})}^{2}+{({r}_{{gxy}}-{r}_{\\mathrm{grp}})}^{2},\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t6\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>where <em>r</em><sub>gxy</sub> is the position of the shared galaxy and <em>r</em><sub>grp</sub> is the group projected spatial centroid. The galaxy is assigned to the group for which <em>R</em><sup>2</sup> is smaller, then the other group's properties are recalculated without that galaxy. We perform no further cuts on minimum velocity distribution or iterate further on membership. The groups with adjusted membership are flagged in Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t2\">2</a>.</p></div></div><h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaa44e7app2\" name=\"apjaa44e7app2\">APPENDIX B: GROUP MEMBERS</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>Here we present the properties of group member galaxies (Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t5\">5</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t6\">6</a>, and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t7\">7</a>). <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t5\"> </a>\n<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t6\"> </a>\n<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t7\"> </a>\n</p><div tabindex=\"-1\" id=\"apjaa44e7t5\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\"><p><b>Table 5.</b>\u00a0\nAlgorithmic Group Members\n</p><table cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"0\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaa44e7t5\" data-toolbar-img=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7t5_lr.gif\" data-toolbar-type=\"table\" data-toolbar-title=\"Table 5\" data-art-data=\"item\" data-art-data-type=\"mrt\"><colgroup><col align=\"left\" char=\"\"></col><col align=\"left\" char=\"\"></col><col align=\"left\" char=\"\"></col><col align=\"left\" char=\"\"></col><col align=\"left\" char=\"\"></col><col align=\"left\" char=\"\"></col></colgroup><thead>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">Field</th>\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">Group</th>\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><em>z</em><sub>gxy</sub></th>\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><em>ez</em><sub>gxy</sub></th>\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">R.A.<sub>gxy</sub></th>\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 7.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f7_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 7.</strong></p><p>Top row: Sky plots for all groups in our algorithmic group catalog. Black points are group members, and gray points are the rest of the galaxies in the field in our redshift catalog (including galaxies in other groups). Group redshifts, group velocity dispersions, and the number of group galaxies are marked. We also show group projected spatial centroids (red cross), <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> (red dashed circle), the lens (red star), and the angular size of 1 Mpc at the redshift of the group (black bar). Bottom row<em>:</em> Velocity histograms for our groups shifted so that the group mean velocity is at 0 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>. Bin widths are 180 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>, which corresponds to about three times the mean redshift error (~0.0002, or ~60 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>) at <em>z</em> = 0.3. Gray histograms are all galaxies in the redshift sample within 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> of the group centroid, and black histograms are group galaxies. The dashed (dotted) vertical lines mark the velocities of the spectroscopic (photometric) redshifts of the lenses in the cases where the lens velocity is within 3000 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> of the group velocity centroid, regardless of whether we identify the lens as a group member. (The complete figure set (269 images) is <a href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7figset7.tar.gz\" id=\"apjaa44e7figset7.tar.gz\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaa44e7figset7.tar.gz\" data-toolbar-title=\"Tarball of figure set images\" data-art-data-content-type=\"Tar file\" data-art-data-type=\"supple-data\">available</a>.)</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaa44e7f7\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f7\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaa44e7f7\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f7\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></div><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 7.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f7_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 7.</strong></p><p>Top row: Sky plots for all groups in our algorithmic group catalog. <main role=\"main\">\n        <!-- Secondary header starts -->\n<div class=\"secondary-header cf\" id=\"wd-secondary-header\">\n    <!-- Branded journal header starts -->\n<div class=\"big-branded\">\n\n    <div class=\"publication-name\" id=\"wd-pub-name\">\n\t<div class=\"publication-title\" itemprop=\"name\" itemid=\"periodical\">\n\t\t\t\t<!-- Journal image link tile starts -->\n<!-- Logo tile starts -->\n<a href=\"/journal/0004-637X\" itemprop=\"url\">\n    <img src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/8febf88b-d09c-11e5-b0b6-759f86a2008e/apj-2016.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The Astrophysical Journal\">\n</a>\n<!-- Logo tile ends -->\n<!-- Journal image link tile ends -->\n</div>\n\t\t</div>\n    <div class=\"partner-logos m-hide\" id=\"wd-partner-logos\">\n            <div class=\"partner-logo-alignment\">\n                <!-- Partner logo tile starts -->\n<a href=\"\" class=\"overlay-launch\">\n    <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/8a2230b8-d09c-11e5-b0b6-759f86a2008e/aas-2018.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The American Astronomical Society, find out more\">\n</a>\n<span class=\"overlay-set\">\n    <div class=\"tint-screen\"></div>\n    <div class=\"overlay-panel\">\n        <a title=\"Close\"  class=\"close-icon close-overlay\" tabindex=\"0\" role=\"button\" aria-describedby=\"close-icon-description\"><span class=\"icon-close\"></span></a>\n        <p id=\"close-icon-description\" class=\"offscreen-hidden\">Click here to close this overlay, or press the \"Escape\" key on your keyboard.</p>\n        <div class=\"overlay-img\">\n            <a href=\"\">\n                <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/8a2230b8-d09c-11e5-b0b6-759f86a2008e/aas-2018.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The American Astronomical Society, find out more\">\n            </a>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"overlay-text\">\n            <p>The American Astronomical Society (AAS), established in 1899 and based in Washington, DC, is the major organization of professional astronomers in North America. Its membership of about 7,000 individuals also includes physicists, mathematicians, geologists, engineers, and others whose research and educational interests lie within the broad spectrum of subjects comprising contemporary astronomy. The mission of the AAS is to enhance and share humanity's scientific understanding of the universe.</p> <p><a href=\"https://aas.org/\">https://aas.org/</a></div>\n        <p class=\"ta-c mt-1 mb-2\"><a href=\"\"></a></p>\n    </div>\n</span>\n<!-- Partner logo tile ends -->\n\n<!-- Partner logo tile starts -->\n<a href=\"\" class=\"overlay-launch\">\n    <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/7ebd1b32-0439-11e9-b401-cfe9679c40e3/iop-2016.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The Institute of Physics, find out more\">\n</a>\n<span class=\"overlay-set\">\n    <div class=\"tint-screen\"></div>\n    <div class=\"overlay-panel\">\n        <a title=\"Close\"  class=\"close-icon close-overlay\" tabindex=\"0\" role=\"button\" aria-describedby=\"close-icon-description\"><span class=\"icon-close\"></span></a>\n        <p id=\"close-icon-description\" class=\"offscreen-hidden\">Click here to close this overlay, or press the \"Escape\" key on your keyboard.</p>\n        <div class=\"overlay-img\">\n            <a href=\"\">\n                <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/7ebd1b32-0439-11e9-b401-cfe9679c40e3/iop-2016.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The Institute of Physics, find out more\">\n            </a>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"overlay-text\">\n            <p>The Institute of Physics (IOP) is a leading scientific society promoting physics and bringing physicists together for the benefit of all. It has a worldwide membership of around 50 000 comprising physicists from all sectors, as well as those with an interest in physics. It works to advance physics research, application and education; and engages with policy makers and the public to develop awareness and understanding of physics. Its publishing company, IOP Publishing, is a world leader in professional scientific communications.</p> <p><a href=\"https://www.iop.org\">https://www.iop.org</a></p></div>\n        <p class=\"ta-c mt-1 mb-2\"><a href=\"\"></a></p>\n    </div>\n</span>\n<!-- Partner logo tile ends -->\n\n<p></p>\n                </div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n<!-- Branded journal header ends -->\n</div> <!-- end secondary-header -->\n<!-- Secondary header ends --><div class=\"da1-da2\" itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/ScholarlyArticle\" id=\"page-content\">\n            <div class=\"da1 ta1 article-head\">\n                <!-- Start Eyebrow block, containing Surtitle and Labels -->\n<div class=\"eyebrow\">\n\t<!-- Start Collection Labels -->\n    <!-- End Collection Labels --> </div>\n<!-- End Eyebrow block -->\n\n<h1 itemprop=\"headline\" class=\"wd-jnl-art-title\">A SPECTROSCOPIC SURVEY OF THE FIELDS OF 28 STRONG GRAVITATIONAL LENSES: THE GROUP CATALOG</h1>\n\n<p class=\"mb-0\">\n\t<span data-authors=\"\">\n\t\t<span itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\" itemprop=\"author\" class=\"nowrap\"><span itemprop=\"name\">Michelle L. class=\"share-icon-link\">\n\t\t\t<img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/icon-google-plus.svg\" alt=\"Share on Google+\">\n\t</a>\n\t</li>\n\t<li id=\"wd-share-icon-mendeley\" class=\"share-icon-link\">\n\t<a href=\"https://www.mendeley.com/import/?doi=10.3847%2F1538-4357%2F833%2F2%2F194\" title=\"Share on Mendeley\" class=\"share-icon-link\">\n\t\t\t<img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/icon-mendeley.svg\" alt=\"Share on Mendeley\">\n\t</a>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"clear-fl\"></div>\n</div>\n\n</div>\n</div>\n            <div class=\"da1 ta1\">\n                <!-- Start Linked Articles note -->\n\t<!-- End Linked Articles note -->\n<!-- Article information starts. This includes author emails, affiliations, article published date, doi etc. -->\n\t<div class=\"reveal-container reveal-closed reveal-plus-icon bdt-1 wd-jnl-art-article-info-wrapper\">\n      \t<div class=\"replica-h3 mt-0\">\n        \t<a id=\"wd-article-info-accordion\" href=\"#\" class=\"reveal-trigger\" data-reveal-label-alt=\"Hide article information\">Article information</a>\n      \t</div>\n      \t<div class=\"reveal-content\">\n        \t<div class=\"article-meta\">\n          \t\t<!-- Start Affiliations --><div class=\"wd-jnl-art-author-affiliations\"><div class=\"replica-h4\">Author affiliations</div><p class=\"mb-05\"><sup>1</sup>   Steward Observatory, University of Arizona, 933 North Cherry Avenue, Tucson, AZ 85721, USA</p><p class=\"mb-05\"><sup>2</sup>   Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Physics Division L-210, 7000 East Avenue, Livermore, CA 94550, USA</p><p class=\"mb-05\"><sup>3</sup>   Space Telescope Science Institute, 3700 San Martin Drive, Baltimore, MD 21218, USA</p><p class=\"mb-05\"><sup>4</sup>   Department of Physics and Astronomy, Texas A&amp;M University-Commerce, Commerce, TX, 75428, USA</p><p class=\"mb-05\"><sup>5</sup>   Department of Physics and Astronomy, Rutgers University, 136 Frelinghuysen Road, Piscataway, NJ 08854, USA</p></div><!-- End Affiliations --><!-- Start ORCIDs --><div class=\"wd-jnl-art-author-orcid-list\"><div class=\"replica-h4\">ORCID iDs</div><p class=\"mb-05\"><span itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\" itemprop=\"author\" class=\"nowrap\"><span itemprop=\"name\">Ann I. Momcheva</span><a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1665-2073\" title=\"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1665-2073\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 256 256\" width=\"20\" class=\"orcid-logo\"><path class=\"st0\" d=\"M256 128c0 70.7-57.3 128-128 128C57.3 256 0 198.7 0 128 0 57.3 57.3 0 128 0 198.7 0 256 57.3 256 128z\"></path><path class=\"st1\" d=\"M86.3 186.2H70.9V79.1h15.4v48.4V186.2z\"></path><path class=\"st1\" d=\"M108.9 79.1h41.6c39.6 0 57 28.3 57 53.6 0 27.5-21.5 53.6-56.8 53.6h-41.8V79.1zM124.3 172.4h24.5c34.9 0 42.9-26.5 42.9-39.7 0-21.5-13.7-39.7-43.7-39.7h-23.7V172.4z\"></path><path class=\"st1\" d=\"M88.7 56.8c0 5.5-4.5 10.1-10.1 10.1 -5.6 0-10.1-4.6-10.1-10.1 0-5.6 4.5-10.1 10.1-10.1C84.2 46.7 88.7 51.3 88.7 56.8z\"></path></svg> https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1665-2073</a></span></p><p class=\"mb-05\"><span itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\" itemprop=\"author\" class=\"nowrap\"><span itemprop=\"name\">Kurtis A.
