type=\"math/tex\">{}_{-1.0}^{+0.7}</script></span></span>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"char\" char=\".\">0.50</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"char\" char=\".\">3</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">\u00a0</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table><p><small>\n<p><strong>Notes.</strong></p>\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn6\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn6\"></a><sup> a</sup>Uncertainties are not calculated for <em>N</em><sub><em>m</em></sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a04.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn7\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn7\"></a><sup> b</sup>Projected distance between the lens and the group centroid.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn8\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn8\"></a><sup> c</sup>Masses are reported when <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1136.gif\" alt=\"$\\geqslant {10}^{13}\\,{M}_{\\odot }$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">\\geqslant {10}^{13}\\,{M}_{\\odot }</script></span></span>.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn9\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn9\"></a><sup> d</sup>(1) <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.1 (groups at lower redshift are most likely not sampled out to <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> because of the spectroscopic field size); (2) <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> intersects the edge of the well-sampled region of the field because the group is large and/or at low <em>z</em>; (3) <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> extends beyond the well-sampled region of the field because the group centroid or several of its members are near the edge of the field; (4) group membership was adjusted manually to remedy overlapping membership.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn10\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn10\"></a><sup> e</sup>Groups in the literature in these fields that have a redshift within 3<em>\u03c3</em><sub><em>z</em></sub> of a group in our catalog. The reference abbreviations are as follows: BHS\u2014Berlind et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib7\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib7\">2006</a>), Haynes et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib27\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib27\">2011</a>), and Smith et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib63\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib63\">2012</a>); and WMKZL06\u2014Williams et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib74\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib74\">2006</a>).\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-ascii\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7t2_ascii.txt?doi=10.3847/1538-4357/833/2/194\" target=\"_blank\">ASCII</a>Typeset images: <a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset-multiple typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7t2_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">1</a> <a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset-multiple typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7t2a_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">2</a> </span></p></div><p>For these groups, we calculate virial masses. There are two ways to determine the masses of structures: via the projected harmonic mean radius (<em>R</em><sub>PV</sub>), and solely via the velocity dispersion. Biviano et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib9\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib9\">2006</a>) find that the <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1137.gif\" alt=\"${M}_{\\mathrm{vir},{R}_{\\mathrm{PV}}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{M}_{\\mathrm{vir},{R}_{\\mathrm{PV}}}</script></span></span> and <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1138.gif\" alt=\"${r}_{\\mathrm{vir},{R}_{\\mathrm{PV}}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{r}_{\\mathrm{vir},{R}_{\\mathrm{PV}}}</script></span></span> are overestimated for small sample sizes, whereas <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1139.gif\" alt=\"${M}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{M}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }</script></span></span> and <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1140.gif\" alt=\"${r}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{r}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }</script></span></span> are not biased.</p><p>As for the virial radius, to approximate the virial mass, we use the formula for <em>M</em><sub>200</sub> derived by Munari et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib55\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib55\">2013</a>) from simulations, fit over the mass range of 10<sup>13</sup>\u00a0<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/lesssim.gif\" alt=\"lesssim\" align=\"baseline\" />\u00a0<em>M</em><sub>200</sub>\u00a0<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/lesssim.gif\" alt=\"lesssim\" align=\"baseline\" /> 10<sup>15</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub>,</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaa44e7eqn4\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7eqn4.gif\" alt=\"Equation (4)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&{M}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }\\approx {M}_{200}=\\displaystyle \\frac{{10}^{15}\\,{M}_{\\odot }}{h(z)}{\\left(\\displaystyle \\frac{{\\sigma }_{\\mathrm{grp}}}{{A}_{1D}}\\right)}^{(1/\\alpha )},\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t4\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>where <em>h</em>(<em>z</em>)\u00a0=\u00a0<em>H</em>(<em>z</em>)/(100 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> Mpc<sup>\u22121</sup>). We take <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1141.gif\" alt=\"${A}_{1{\\rm{D}}}\\,=1177$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{A}_{1{\\rm{D}}}\\,=1177</script></span></span> km s<sup>\u22121</sup> and <em>\u03b1</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.364 from their simulations using AGN feedback and galaxy tracers. Compared to these, <em>R</em><sub>PV</sub>-based virial masses (<span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1142.gif\" alt=\"${M}_{\\mathrm{vir},{R}_{\\mathrm{PV}}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{M}_{\\mathrm{vir},{R}_{\\mathrm{PV}}}</script></span></span>) using the equations of Girardi et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib24\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib24\">1998</a>) and Limber &amp; Mathews (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib41\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib41\">1960</a>) are systematically higher by ~0.6 dex over most of the mass range of our final catalog. This offset creates a high-mass tail that consists of 14 groups with <em>M</em><sub>vir</sub>\u00a0&gt;\u00a010<sup>15</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub> for 0.2\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5 that is not in agreement with the high-mass slope of the Millennium-XXL (MXXL) cosmological simulation (Angulo et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib2\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib2\">2012</a>) given any arbitrary volume normalization (see Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s4-2-3\">4.2.3</a>). Furthermore, <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1143.gif\" alt=\"${r}_{\\mathrm{vir},{R}_{\\mathrm{PV}}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{r}_{\\mathrm{vir},{R}_{\\mathrm{PV}}}</script></span></span> is about 1.5 times larger than both <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1144.gif\" alt=\"${r}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{r}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }</script></span></span> and that expected for NFW halos.</p><p>Thus, our data support the conclusions of Biviano et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib9\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib9\">2006</a>) and motivate our use of <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1145.gif\" alt=\"${r}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{r}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }</script></span></span> and <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1146.gif\" alt=\"${M}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{M}_{\\mathrm{vir},\\sigma }</script></span></span>. These choices differ from those made in Ammons et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib1\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib1\">2014</a>), who calculate <em>R</em><sub>PV</sub> and <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1147.gif\" alt=\"${M}_{\\mathrm{vir},{R}_{\\mathrm{PV}}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{M}_{\\mathrm{vir},{R}_{\\mathrm{PV}}}</script></span></span>.</p><p>We only report masses \u226510<sup>13</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub>. The <em>M</em><sub>vir</sub> relation we adopt has not been calibrated for lower masses. Lower masses (i.e., those in the range normally expected for single massive galaxy halos rather than virialized groups) are likely to be underestimated because of the incomplete group member identification.</p><p>All uncertainties in group quantities are calculated using a bootstrap method with 1000 iterations. We resample with replacement of the identified group members and recalculate the group properties using the resampled members. We then subtract the median value of each property over all the iterations and find the 16th and 84th percentile values, which are listed in the tables with the properties measured using all the algorithmically identified group members.</p><p>Our group catalog and individual group memberships are likely to be somewhat incomplete, although we show below that our catalog reproduces the distributions of group kinematic properties and the fraction of group members to field galaxies of other catalogs in the literature (Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s4-2\">4.2</a>). Here we perform a simple test of how incompleteness might affect the derived group centroids, velocity dispersions, and masses. For the 32 groups with at least 20 members, we randomly select 25%, 50%, and 75% of their members without replacement 1000 times and find the median group parameter values. For all three incompleteness levels, the median values are within three standard deviations of the original values using the previously calculated uncertainties, although the effect can be systematic and does not account for groups whose incompleteness would have precluded their identification in the first place. For 25% completeness, the velocity dispersions are underestimated (see Zabludoff &amp; Mulchaey <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib79\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib79\">1998</a>) by a median of 3% and the masses by a median of 9%. We note that the groups with at least 20 members are well sampled and/or rich compared with the other groups in our catalog. The 20+ member groups have a median velocity dispersion of 630 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> compared with the median of 350 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> for the full sample of 5+ member groups. However, there is considerable overlap in the velocity dispersion ranges of these two samples, 290\u20131180 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> compared with 60\u20131200 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> for the 20+ and 5+ member groups, respectively. More importantly, the systematic offset between the measured velocity dispersion for the full 20+ member groups and for the 25% completeness subsamples does not depend on velocity dispersion; the velocity dispersion is generally underestimated in the 25% subsamples within one standard deviation over the full range of velocity dispersions. Hence, we conclude that the impact of incompleteness, even on the lower sigma groups in our catalog, falls generally within the stated errors.</p><p>While we make choices to avoid fragmenting rich clusters with substructure, distinct but neighboring structures might also be artificially combined, resulting in more high-velocity dispersion (higher mass) groups in our catalog than expected. Thus, we examine the four clusters with <em>M</em><sub>vir</sub>\u00a0\u2265\u00a010<sup>15</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub> in our catalog to evaluate whether they are probably real or are the artificial combination of multiple groups and/or large-scale structure.</p><p>To do so, we verify if these groups are stable to changes in the velocity dispersion initial guess by comparing them in our catalog to that created using a initial velocity dispersion of 500 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>. Of the four massive clusters, three are identical in both catalogs, and the other has group parameters that agree within the 3<em>\u03c3</em> uncertainties. Additionally, three of these four have red sequences in their color\u2013magnitude diagrams that suggest evolved clusters. The other might have a red sequence, but it is at low redshift and is thus poorly sampled. One of these also is a supergroup (see Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-2\">5.2</a>).</p><p>We also look at the 16 groups with the most bimodal member galaxy velocity distributions to determine whether each velocity peak corresponds to a distinct substructure on the sky. There is only one group that displays a well-defined distinction; we identify this group as a supergroup (see Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-2\">5.2</a>).</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s3-2\" name=\"apjaa44e7s3-2\">3.2.\u00a0Comparison to Visual Identification</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>Early visual identification was used to construct a target group catalog for refining our group finding algorithm. Two of us (A.I.Z. and M.L.W.) studied the galaxy velocity histograms as well as the individual galaxy velocities and projected spatial positions in each field. We identified likely groups in 1500 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> wide velocity bins in which at least 5 (A.I.Z.) or 10 (M.L.W.) galaxies were clustered on the sky relative to the surveyed field.</p><p>We used cases where our algorithm did not find visually identified groups to guide our parameter tuning and to understand the intrinsic limitations of the algorithm for this sample (e.g., the difficulty of identifying groups at higher redshifts). This check of course assumes that everything we identify visually is a real structure.</p><p>Our algorithm identifies visually identified groups in 69% of the peaks with at least 5 galaxies (91% of the peaks with at least 10 galaxies) and with strong clustering in both R.A. and decl. There are two possible general types of failures: the algorithm could be missing real structures that are well represented in our data (algorithm failure), or the algorithm could be missing structures because they are inadequately sampled (data failure). The visually identified groups that are not identified by the algorithm are typically located near the field edges, at higher redshift, or are located in regions of their field that are more densely sampled, which artificially causes the galaxies to appear clustered. Thus, data failure is the dominant cause for our algorithm to fail in identifying all our visually identified groups. Of all the velocity peaks in which our algorithm identifies structures, 11% were not visually identified. These groups do not have different properties than others found both visually and by our algorithm, except for those that have fewer members than we identified visually (the algorithmically identified groups with three and four members).</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s3-3\" name=\"apjaa44e7s3-3\">3.3.\u00a0Additional Candidate Groups</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>Our magnitude-limited, multi-object spectroscopy is less successful at higher redshifts and in overdense cluster cores; this reduces the efficacy of our group-finding algorithm. To include additional structures for future spectroscopic follow-up or modeling in these fields, we create a supplemental candidate group catalog from our visual identifications. We focus on 58 single-redshift bins with \u226510 galaxies clustered on the sky. For the additional candidate groups, we apply a simple 3<em>\u03c3</em> clipping procedure (Yahil &amp; Vidal <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib78\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib78\">1977</a>) to the galaxy redshift distribution within the bin to estimate group membership. We use no projected spatial criteria in this case. Once the 3<em>\u03c3</em> clipping converges, we calculate the group virial radius. We then discard any members projected more than 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> from the projected spatial centroid and recalculate all the group properties, including <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>.</p><p>Four groups converge that include galaxies that have previously been assigned membership to algorithmically selected groups (2 candidate group members in one case, 3 members in two cases, and all 13 members in one case). These galaxies are removed from the candidate groups, the group properties are recalculated, and the 3 that remain in the final catalog are flagged accordingly. Of the 58 redshift bins, 26 are rejected because their memberships did not converge or converged into groups with fewer than 3 members, they had fewer than 3 members within 3<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>, or they overlapped completely with a group in our algorithmic catalog.</p><p>We check the remaining groups with the most distinctly bimodal velocity distributions to determine whether they are separable on the sky; none have a velocity substructure that corresponds to distinct spatial substructure, therefore we do not remove any groups. Since the mean pairwise radial velocities at <em>r</em>\u00a0~\u00a01 Mpc for dark and luminous matter at 0\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a01 are around 200 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> in the simulations of Weinberg et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib72\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib72\">2004</a>), we discard an additional 9 candidate groups with <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a0200 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>, as they could be merely cuts through filaments or sheets of galaxies rather than virialized groups.</p><p>We are left with 23 non-algorithmically selected candidate groups in our supplemental catalog. While we do not use color information to identify these structures, five have red-sequence-like galaxy overdensities in color\u2013magnitude space. Thus, while incomplete sampling might make their identification and characterization more difficult, their assigned candidate group members very likely do trace evolved structures.</p><p>There are some redshift bins at higher redshift with fewer than 10 galaxies, but no identified groups. These are most likely parts of rich structures, since there are overdensities where our sensitivity is low. These peaks are in field b1422 at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a00.78, in field b1600 at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a00.77, in field he1104 at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a00.73, and in field sbs1520 at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a00.72 and 0.82. While we have enough galaxies in these redshift bins that there are noticeable peaks, we do not have enough to calculate meaningful candidate group quantities. We therefore make no further attempt to include them.</p></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaa44e7s4\" name=\"apjaa44e7s4\">4.\u00a0TESTING THE GROUP CATALOG</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>We perform tests to evaluate the quality of the group catalog produced by the group-finding algorithm.</p><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s4-1\" name=\"apjaa44e7s4-1\">4.1.\u00a0Comparison of Individual Groups to the Literature</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We compare our algorithmic catalog to group samples in the literature that overlap our fields. As the methods for identifying structures differ, this comparison tests the robustness of our catalog.</p><p>We compare our groups to groups and clusters in the NED within 20' of our field centers with spectroscopic redshifts that are not from previous work by our group. We consider a NED structure to be found if our group has a redshift within 3<em>\u03c3</em><sub><em>z</em></sub> of the NED spectroscopic value. We do not compare other group properties, because ways of calculating them vary widely, they are not uniformly reported, and the survey footprints vary in size and position on the sky.</p><p>Three groups from NED that we do not recover are at redshifts that are either too high (2) or too low (1) to be readily detected given our redshift survey sensitivity, and four are in regions of their fields where we have little to no spectroscopic coverage. Of the remaining 26 entries, we find 17. For another 5, we find either substructures of the previously reported group, or we combine known groups into one. We fail to find 4 groups. We explain this below.</p><p>Below we discuss those of our fields with groups listed in the NED.</p><p><em>b1600</em>: Auger et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib3\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib3\">2007</a>) find four groups in this field in their redshift sample of 40 galaxies. We find a group at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a00.29 (0.2893<span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1148.gif\" alt=\"${}_{-0.0004}^{+0.0005}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{}_{-0.0004}^{+0.0005}</script></span></span> that agrees with their 0.291 group within their reported precision). We also find a group similar to their <em>z</em> = 0.415 group (<em>z</em><sub>grp</sub> = 0.4146\u00a0\u00b1\u00a00.0002); five of our six group galaxies are added to our redshift sample from their work via the NED. We do not identify groups at <em>z</em> = 0.540 or 0.623, as they do; none of the galaxy redshifts from their <em>z</em> = 0.291, 0.540, or 0.623 groups are in Momcheva et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib52\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib52\">2015</a>).</p><p><em>h12531</em>: We find a group at <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub> = 0.0531<span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1149.gif\" alt=\"${}_{-0.0008}^{+0.0007}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{}_{-0.0008}^{+0.0007}</script></span></span>, a similar redshift to Abell 3528 of the Shapley Supercluster (which has three entries in the NED at similar redshifts). Our group is very likely part of this larger cluster and has 13 of 22 member galaxies that have redshifts from the NED. Since the Abell cluster centroid is at the very edge of our field, we caution that the properties for our group might not be well determined.</p><p><em>hst14113</em>: We recover a group at <em>z</em> = 0.0808\u00a0\u00b1\u00a00.0008, near the <em>z</em> = 0.0809 group reported by Miller et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib50\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib50\">2005</a>); 2 of our 26 members have redshifts added from the NED.</p><p>We also recover part of the 3C 295 cluster originally identified by Dressler &amp; Gunn (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib18\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib18\">1992</a>) at <em>z</em> = 0.4599 with 112 galaxies and a velocity dispersion of 1300 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>. We recover a group with 55 galaxies at slightly higher redshift (but still within the uncertainties: <em>z</em> = 0.4603\u00a0\u00b1\u00a00.0003) and 2 small groups at slightly lower redshift (7 and 6 members at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a0<span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1150.gif\" alt=\"${0.4504}_{-0.0012}^{+0.0009}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{0.4504}_{-0.0012}^{+0.0009}</script></span></span> and <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1151.gif\" alt=\"${0.4592}_{-0.0003}^{+0.0004}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{0.4592}_{-0.0003}^{+0.0004}</script></span></span>, respectively). In our structures, only 9 galaxies (4 of 7 members of the <em>z</em> = 0.4504 group and 5 of 55 members of the <em>z</em> = 0.4603 group) are added from the NED.</p><p><em>lbq1333</em>: We find a group at <em>z</em> = 0.0856\u00a0\u00b1\u00a00.0003, near the <em>z</em> = 0.085 group reported by McConnachie et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib46\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib46\">2009</a>); three of the five members have redshifts from the NED.</p><p><em>mg0751</em>: the NED lists three groups with <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a00.0266. Although we are relatively insensitive to structures at such low redshift, we identify a group of four galaxies at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a0<span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1152.gif\" alt=\"${0.0265}_{-0.0001}^{+0.0002};$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{0.0265}_{-0.0001}^{+0.0002};</script></span></span> one of these members has a redshift from the NED.</p><p><em>mg1549</em>: We identify a group at <em>z</em> = 0.0709, as reported by Lopes et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib43\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib43\">2009</a>); three of our seven members are from the NED.</p><p><em>pg1115</em>: We find a structure at <em>z</em> = 0.1600, like that reported by Barkhouse et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib6\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib6\">2006</a>) and Mason et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib45\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib45\">2000</a>), including 6 (of 11) galaxies with redshifts from the NED.</p><p>We do not recover a group at <em>z</em> = 0.477 that has been attributed to WARPS-II by Mullis et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib54\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib54\">2003</a>), but the more recent WARPS-II catalog of Horner et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib29\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib29\">2008</a>) reports a redshift of 0.4859, where we do find a group; none of the 11 members have redshifts from the NED.</p><p>Carrasco et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib13\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib13\">2007</a>) find a cluster at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.485 made up of at least 2 substructures along the line of sight. We recover the substructure redshifts at <em>z</em> = 0.48218 and 0.49191 (our <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0=\u00a0<span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1153.gif\" alt=\"${0.4819}_{-0.0006}^{+0.0007}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{0.4819}_{-0.0006}^{+0.0007}</script></span></span> and <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1154.gif\" alt=\"${0.4922}_{-0.0005}^{+0.0007}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{0.4922}_{-0.0005}^{+0.0007}</script></span></span>), but we do not find these 2 to be part of some larger cluster. All but 3 of the galaxies in these 2 of our groups (of 25 total members) are added from the NED.</p><p><em>rxj1131</em>: Tucker et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib70\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib70\">2000</a>) list 4 groups at <em>z</em> = 0.0534, 0.0966, 0.1014, and 0.1032. We find a group at <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1155.gif\" alt=\"${0.0531}_{-0.0003}^{+0.0007}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{0.0531}_{-0.0003}^{+0.0007}</script></span></span>, consistent with their lowest redshift group; none of our group members have redshifts from the NED. We also recover a group at <em>z</em> = 0.1021\u00a0\u00b1\u00a00.0004, which is a combination of their other 3 groups, but has a redshift within 3<em>\u03c3</em><sub><em>z</em></sub> of their 2 higher redshift groups; 7 of the 66 galaxies in our group are from the NED.</p><p><em>sbs1520</em>: Auger et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib4\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib4\">2008</a>) find 3 groups (<em>z</em> = 0.716, 0.758, and 0.818). We only identify a group that is similar to the middle one; all 6 of our members are added from Auger et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib4\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib4\">2008</a>). Our group at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a0<span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7ieqn1156.gif\" alt=\"${0.7590}_{-0.0006}^{+0.0004}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{0.7590}_{-0.0006}^{+0.0004}</script></span></span> is much smaller than theirs (6 group galaxies to their 13). One complication is that we do not include the lens galaxy in our sample, because its redshift is ambiguous, while they do and assign it to this group. The most likely cause for the discrepancy, however, is their more permissive spatial selection. We are capable of recovering groups similar to their groups at <em>z</em> = 0.716 and 0.818 if we accept galaxies up to 5<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> from the group centroid, which may not be bound to the group.</p><p>In summary, our group finder finds groups that are similar but not always identical to those in the literature in most cases.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s4-2\" name=\"apjaa44e7s4-2\">4.2.\u00a0Statistical Comparison of Group Properties to the Literature</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>While it is valuable to compare specific cases to ensure that our algorithm can recover previously reported structures, we also test whether the statistical properties of our group catalog are similar to those described elsewhere. Although we only discuss our algorithmic catalog here, including our non-algorithmic candidate groups does not significantly affect these comparisons.</p><h4 id=\"apjaa44e7s4-2-1\" name=\"apjaa44e7s4-2-1\">4.2.1.\u00a0Distribution of Group Velocity Dispersions</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We compare our group catalog to that of zCOSMOS (Knobel et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib37\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib37\">2012</a>) for groups with reported velocity dispersions and 0.2\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5. We limit both samples to those with at least five spectroscopic members.</p><p>Using a Kolmogorov\u2013Smirnov (K-S) test, we find that the resulting distributions of the velocity dispersions of the two catalogs are not distinguishable at the 95% confidence level (see Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f1\">1</a>).</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaa44e7f1\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaa44e7f1\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f1_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 1.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 1.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f1_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 1.</strong>\u00a0Comparison of the distribution of velocity dispersions between our group catalog (black histogram) and that of zCOSMOS (shaded gray histogram). For both catalogs, we select groups with 0.2\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5 with at least five spectroscopically identified members and reported velocity dispersions. These distributions cannot be distinguished at the 95% confidence limit using a K-S test.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaa44e7f1\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f1\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaa44e7f1\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f1\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure></div><h4 id=\"apjaa44e7s4-2-2\" name=\"apjaa44e7s4-2-2\">4.2.2.\u00a0Frequency of Significant Substructure</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>For those of our groups with at least 10 members, we test for substructure using the Dressler\u2013Shectman test (Dressler &amp; Shectman <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib19\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib19\">1988</a>). This test calculates the difference between the average velocity of a galaxy and its nearest neighbors as projected on the sky compared with the mean velocity of the entire structure, as well as the difference between the local and global velocity dispersion. Spatial overdensities that correspond to velocity overdensities indicate substructure. We use 5000 Monte Carlo shuffles when calculating the probability that the Dressler\u2013Shectman statistic \u0394 is observed by chance. Of our main group sample with 0.2\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5, 55 groups have at least 10 members. Substructure is detected for 21 of these 55 groups (38%) at the <em>P</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.05 significance level.</p><p>Restricting our sample to only consider groups with at least 20 members (23 groups) and identifying <em>P</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.01 as significant, as do Hou et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib30\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib30\">2012</a>), we find six have substructure (26%), in good agreement with the 27% (four of 15) found by Hou et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib30\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib30\">2012</a>).</p></div><h4 id=\"apjaa44e7s4-2-3\" name=\"apjaa44e7s4-2-3\">4.2.3.\u00a0Distribution of Group Masses</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We compare our group mass function to that of the Millennium-XXL (MXXL) Simulation (see Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f2\">2</a>). MXXL is a high-resolution large-volume cosmological <em>N</em>-body simulation aimed at studying simulated cluster properties (Angulo et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib2\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib2\">2012</a>). We calculate the mass function of our algorithmic catalog for the groups with 0.2\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5, <em>N</em><sub><em>m</em></sub>\u00a0\u2265\u00a05, and <em>M</em><sub>vir</sub>\u00a0\u2265\u00a010<sup>13</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub>.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaa44e7f2\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaa44e7f2\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f2_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 2.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 2.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f2_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 2.</strong>\u00a0Comparison of our mass function for groups with <em>N</em><sub><em>m</em></sub>\u00a0\u2265\u00a05 and 0.2\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5 (black points) with the Millennium Simulation mass functions (gray curves) at <em>z</em> = 0.2 (solid) and 0.5 (dotted). Bins are independent. Black error bars are the 1<em>\u03c3</em> spread in the number of groups in a bin (not the error on the mean) using 1000 bootstrap realizations of our group masses and Poisson statistics. Gray error bars are the expected uncertainty in the observed counts that is due to cosmic variance given the simulation mass function at <em>z</em> = 0.2 using the Cosmic Variance Calculator (Trenti &amp; Stiavelli <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib69\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib69\">2008</a>). The black points are normalized arbitrarily along the vertical axis so that the high-mass slope can be compared with the models (see text for details). The two highest mass bins do not have any observed groups, which is consistent with the model given the shot noise. The high-mass slope of our mass function agrees within the uncertainties with that of the simulation. Provided the normalization is reasonable, we therefore reliably find high-mass structures. Our catalog begins to suffer from incompleteness at masses lower than ~10<sup>14</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub>.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaa44e7f2\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f2\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaa44e7f2\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f2\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>We wish to test (1) the shape of our mass function at high masses, where our group sample should be mostly complete, and (2) at which lower masses our sample is incomplete. Our mass function needs to be normalized by the volume probed by our sample to compare it to the simulations. However, because our redshift sample is not volume limited and there are large variations in spectroscopic completeness over each individual field and among fields, this normalization is not straightforward. Therefore, we searched for a normalization that allows the mass distribution shape to match the simulations in the highest mass bins and that represents a reasonable effective sample volume. We select a normalization using a <em>\u03c7</em><sup>2</sup> fit of the data at <em>M</em>\u00a0<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/gsim.gif\" alt=\"gsim\" align=\"baseline\" />\u00a010<sup>14</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub> assuming a two-sided Gaussian for the uncertainties in the data. The resulting fit has a <em>\u03c7</em><sup>2</sup>\u00a0~ 1 and a ~5' radius circular footprint per field. This footprint size corresponds to the 5' radius regions around the lenses that have the highest spectroscopic completenesses. Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f2\">2</a> shows this normalization of our data, which matches the simulations at high masses and also predicts a sensible field size. We conclude that the matched normalization is reasonable.</p><p>We calculate the simulation mass function using the Millennium Simulation cosmology and the fitting function of Angulo et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib2\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib2\">2012</a>) using HMFcalc (Murray et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib56\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib56\">2013</a>). We calculate their mass functions for <em>z</em> = 0.2 and <em>z</em> = 0.5 to bracket the redshift range for which we calculate our mass function. Our high-mass tail slope agrees with that of MXXL to within the uncertainties. Thus, we conclude that the number of high-mass objects we find is in agreement with theoretical expectations, provided the normalization of our mass function is reasonable, above roughly 10<sup>14</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub>. Our mass function turns over at masses ~10<sup>14</sup> <em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub> and lower, indicating incompleteness in our group catalog at these masses.</p></div><h4 id=\"apjaa44e7s4-2-4\" name=\"apjaa44e7s4-2-4\">4.2.4.\u00a0Fraction of Galaxies in Groups</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>For our algorithmic group catalog, we calculate the fraction of all galaxies that are group members and compare it to the literature.</p><p>Carlberg et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib12\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib12\">2001</a>) find over similar redshift (0.1\u20130.6) and velocity dispersion (40\u2013700 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>) ranges that 691 of 3290 (21%\u00a0\u00b1\u00a01%, assuming Poisson errors) of their galaxies lie in groups of at least three members, where membership is defined within 1.5<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> of the group centroid. To make a fair comparison, we consider our algorithmic groups with three or more members and similarly limit their membership to within 1.5<em>r</em><sub>vir</sub>. We find that 1837 of our 9432 galaxies (19.5%\u00a0\u00b1\u00a00.5%) are group members, consistent with Carlberg et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib12\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib12\">2001</a>).</p></div></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaa44e7s5\" name=\"apjaa44e7s5\">5.\u00a0RESULTS</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><h3 id=\"apjaa44e7s5-1\" name=\"apjaa44e7s5-1\">5.1.\u00a0Group Catalog Properties</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We present the group catalog in Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t2\">2</a>, present group member galaxies in Appendix <xref summary=\"alaxies in Appendix B (Table \">B</xref> (Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t5\">5</a>), plot the redshift and velocity dispersion distributions in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f3\">3</a>, and plot redshift histograms for each field in Figure Set <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f4\">4</a>. We also include sky plots and velocity histograms for each group in Appendix <xref summary=\"h group in Appendix C (Figure Set \">C</xref> (Figure Set <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f7\">7</a>).<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f3\"> </a>\n<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f4\"> </a>\n</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaa44e7f3\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaa44e7f3\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f3_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 3.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 3.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f3_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 3.</strong>\u00a0Velocity dispersion and redshift distributions for our group sample. Upper left: we show groups with at least five members (filled circles), those with three and four members (open circles), and the additional group candidates that are not found by our algorithm, but are visually identified (open triangles; see Sections <a class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s3-3\">3.3</a> and <a class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-1\">5.1</a>). Open red squares denote the mean <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub> derived from the filled circles; their red horizontal error bars show the 0.1 redshift bin width and vertical error bars the standard error in the mean. Lower left: redshift distributions for the 3+ member group sample (open histogram), the 5+ member group sample (solid black), and the additional group candidate sample (solid gray). The dip at <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0~\u00a00.4 corresponds to a decrease in the number of galaxy redshifts measured (see Figure\u00a06 of Momcheva et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib52\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib52\">2015</a>), which is most likely due to the Ca H and K absorption lines coinciding with the [O <span class=\"small-caps\">i</span>] 5577 \u00c5 sky line. Upper right: velocity dispersion distributions for the same three samples. Our group catalog spans a range of velocity dispersions and redshifts, although most are in the 100 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a0600 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> and 0.05\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.55 ranges. The dearth of higher redshift groups arises in part from the difficulty of spectroscopically sampling faint overdense group cores. The differences between the algorithmically selected and the supplemental visually identified samples are discussed in Sections <a class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s3-3\">3.3</a> and <a class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-1\">5.1</a>.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaa44e7f3\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f3\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaa44e7f3\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f3\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaa44e7f4\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaa44e7f4\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f4_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 4.\" data-art-data=\"item\" data-art-data-type=\"fig-set\"><div class=\"figure-apjaa44e7f4-1\" style=\"display:none;\"><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; The top two panels are the R.A. (top) and decl. (middle) offsets from the center of the field in Mpc at the redshift of the galaxy; the opening angles of the beams are exaggerated to show structure. The bottom panel shows the redshift distribution of the sample in redshift bins 0.01 wide, which corresponds to ~2000 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.3. The gray points and open histograms denote all the galaxies in our redshift catalog, the black circles and solid black histograms show the galaxies in our algorithmic group catalog (those listed in Tables <a class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t1\">1</a> and <a class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t2\">2</a>), and the small black points and the solid gray histograms are our non-algorithmic candidate groups (Table <a class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t4\">4</a>). The large peak with the horizontally shaded histogram in field b0712 at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a00.29 is the supergroup discussed in Section <a class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-2\">5.2</a>, Table <a class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t3\">3</a>, and Figure <a href=\"#apjaa44e7f5\">5</a>. The black dashed and dotted vertical lines indicate spectroscopic and photometric lens redshifts, respectively. The dotted curves are redshift selection functions arbitrarily normalized based on each field's most populated redshift bin. These functions are calculated using the spectroscopic field size and based on how the spectroscopic completeness varies over our I-band magnitude range for a homogeneous universe using the luminosity functions of Faber et al. (<a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib20\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib20\">2007</a>) for 0\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a01, as in Ammons et al. (<a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib1\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib1\">2014</a>). These functions suggest where in redshift the spectroscopic samples for each field are most sensitive. Even when a group is not found at <em>z</em><sub>lens</sub>, there usually is more than one galaxy present. (The complete figure set (26 images) is <a href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7figset4.tar.gz\" id=\"apjaa44e7figset4.tar.gz\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaa44e7figset4.tar.gz\" data-toolbar-title=\"Tarball of figure set images\" data-art-data-content-type=\"Tar file\" data-art-data-type=\"supple-data\">available</a>.)</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaa44e7f4\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f4\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaa44e7f4\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f4\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></div><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 4.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f4_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 4.</strong></p><p>Redshift histograms for the 26 fields we include in our group catalog. The large peak with the horizontally shaded histogram in field b0712 at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a00.29 is the supergroup discussed in Section <a class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-2\">5.2</a>, Table <a class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t3\">3</a>, and Figure <a href=\"#apjaa44e7f5\">5</a>. (<a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib20\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib20\">2007</a>) for 0\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a01, as in Ammons et al. (<a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib1\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib1\">2014</a>). These functions suggest where in redshift the spectroscopic samples for each field are most sensitive. Even when a group is not found at <em>z</em><sub>lens</sub>, there usually is more than one galaxy present. (The complete figure set (26 images) is <a href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7figset4.tar.gz\" id=\"apjaa44e7figset4.tar.gz\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaa44e7figset4.tar.gz\" data-toolbar-title=\"Tarball of figure set images\" data-art-data-content-type=\"Tar file\" data-art-data-type=\"supple-data\">available</a>.)</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaa44e7f4\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f4\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaa44e7f4\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaa44e7f4\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure><div class=\"reveal-container reveal-closed reveal-plus-icon bdt-1 reveal-enabled\" id=\"figset\"><div class=\"replica-h3 mt-0\"><a data-reveal-label-alt=\"Hide figure set (26 panels)\" class=\"reveal-trigger figureset-trigger\" tabindex=\"0\" data-reveal-text=\"View figure set (26 panels)\">View figure set (26 panels)</a></div><div class=\"reveal-content\"><div class=\"overflow-x figureset\"></div><span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-trb-apjaa44e7f4\" class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-tarball\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7figset4.tar.gz\"><span class=\"icon-file-zip\"></span>Tarball of figure set images</a></span></div></div></figure><p>In our algorithmic group catalog, we find 210 groups with at least 5 member galaxies, 186 of which are at <em>z</em>\u00a0\u2265\u00a00.1. At redshifts below 0.1, our fields are not large enough to sample out to <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> for any but the smallest groups. We therefore present groups at <em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.1 with the caveat that the group properties, especially the group projected spatial centroid, might be poorly determined. Of the 210 at all redshifts, 187 have not previously been identified in the NED either by other authors or in work using earlier versions of our redshift catalog (Williams et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib74\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib74\">2006</a>). We identify groups at 0.04\u00a0\u2264\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a00.76 with our range of greatest sensitivity at 0.2\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5 and a median at <em>z</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.31. Our groups have 60 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>\u00a0\u2264\u00a0<em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0\u2264\u00a01200 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>, with most (84%) with 100 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a0600 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>. The median value is <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub> = 350 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>.</p><p>From our experiments with our group algorithm (see Appendix <xref summary=\"rithm (see Appendix A.1), we are not confid\">A.1</xref>), we are not confident in the robustness of groups of three to four galaxies. Using geometric simulations of large-scale structure, Ramella et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaa44e7bib59\" id=\"fnref-apjaa44e7bib59\">1997</a>) estimate that 50%\u201375% of their groups with three members are not gravitationally bound systems, while only 10%\u201330% of five or more member groups are spurious. As our algorithm only searches for groups in velocity bins and grid squares with at least five galaxies, three- and four-member groups are found only when there is another group at a similar redshift and position on the sky or when field galaxies are located nearby. However, we tabulate three- and four-member groups for completeness and for the information of future observational follow-up and gravitational lens modeling. We find 59 groups with three or four members at 0.03\u00a0\u2264\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a00.76 and a median redshift of 0.33. These groups have 20 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>\u00a0&lt; <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a0270 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> and a median of 140 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>.</p><p>We find one supergroup that we discuss in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7s5-2\">5.2</a> and present in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t3\">3</a>, Appendix <xref summary=\", Appendix B (Table \">B</xref> (Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t6\">6</a>), and Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f5\">5</a>.<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t3\"> </a>\n</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaa44e7f5\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaa44e7f5\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f5_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 5.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 5.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/833/2/194/Full/apjaa44e7f5_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 5.</strong>\u00a0Top row: sky plots for the entire supergroup (leftmost column) and its three main substructures (other columns) in field b0712. Black points are group members, and gray points are the rest of the galaxies in the field in our redshift sample. Group redshifts, group velocity dispersions, and the number of group galaxies are marked. We also show the group projected spatial centroid (red cross), <em>r</em><sub>vir</sub> (red dotted circle), the lens (red star), and the angular size of 1 Mpc at the redshift of the group (black bar). Bottom row: Velocity histograms for these structures shifted so that the group mean velocity is at 0 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>. Bin widths are 180 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>, which corresponds to about three times the mean redshift error (~0.0002, or ~60 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>) at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.3. Gray histograms are the full sample for the field, and black histograms are group galaxies. The group finder locates substructures that correspond to distinct regions both on the sky and in velocity.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block group centroid.\n<a name=\"apjaa44e7fn13\" id=\"apjaa44e7fn13\"></a><sup> b</sup>Mass assuming virialization.\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-ascii\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7t3_ascii.txt?doi=10.3847/1538-4357/833/2/194\" target=\"_blank\">ASCII</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/833/2/194/suppdata/apjaa44e7t3_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">Typeset image</a></span></p></div><p>We present 23 additional candidate groups in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t4\">4</a>, Appendix <xref summary=\", Appendix B (Table \">B</xref> (Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t7\">7</a>), and Appendix <xref summary=\"), and Appendix C (Figure Set \">C</xref> (Figure Set <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaa44e7f8\">8</a>) that were not identified by the algorithm. They span a range of 0.16\u00a0\u2264\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a00.66 with a median of 0.42, 220 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>\u00a0&lt; <em>\u03c3</em><sub>grp</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a01010 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> with a median of 490 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>, and their median number of members is eight. The additional groups have on average somewhat higher velocity dispersions and mean redshifts than the <em>N</em><sub><em>m</em></sub>\u00a0\u2265\u00a05 groups selected by our algorithm. Even at a given redshift, the non-algorithmic groups tend to have higher velocity dispersions. These differences arise from the sorts of groups we select with each method. We require at least 10 galaxies to be at a similar redshift to identify a possible non-algorithmic group where there is no algorithmic group. This choice selects for the richer groups missed by the algorithm. Non-algorithmic groups tend to have higher average redshifts, mainly because we only report those not found by our algorithm and the algorithm identifies most of the groups at low redshift.<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaa44e7t4\"> </a>\n</p><div tabindex=\"-1\" id=\"apjaa44e7t4\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\"><p><b>Table align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{}_{-110}^{+130}</script></span></span>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"right\">5.0<span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\"
